<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Claimed to Have Put 4,000 Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean forces had put some 4,000
 Ethiopian soldiers out of action since the two Horn of African
nations exchanged fires from Friday along the Mereb-Setit front,
the Eritrean Foreign Ministry said in a press release Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Aggregate Ethiopian losses in the two-day fighting were 850
Ethiopian soldiers killed, 3,100 wounded and 13 taken prisoners,"
said the release.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian air force again bombed Eritrea's Assab airport, a
 strategic military target, on Saturday and Sunday morning,
Ethiopia announced in Addis Ababa Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean Foreign Ministry said "there were no human
casualties or damage to property in both bombings, which seemed
to target the civilian airport of Assab."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an announcement made by Ethiopia Saturday morning
claimed that "in the two days of fighting, 5,950 Eritrean
soldiers have been killed, captured and wounded."
</P>
<P>
Friday's offensive came after a one-week lull in hostilities.
The two countries had been in intense fighting around the Mereb
River from June 9 to 17.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long fighting, Ethiopian claimed its forces had
put over 24,450 Eritrean soldiers out of action, while Eritrea
said its troops killed or wounded more than 18,000 Ethiopian
soldiers, and destroyed four Mig fighters and a helicopter gun
ship.
</P>
<P>
The border war between the two countries broke out in early
May, 1998 over a disputed stretch of their border area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
