<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, June 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak seems to
move toward a narrow government after signing a coalition
agreement with the left-wing Meretz party, making it the third
coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which was signed late Saturday night,
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid will become education minister in the
new cabinet. The party will also get portfolioes of the trade and
industry ministry. (BC-Israel-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Thousands of Israelis in the north blocked major
road junctions on Sunday as part of their strike over the security
and economic situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
A group of representatives of the demonstrators, including some
local council members, gathered in front of the Prime Minister
Office in Jerusalem to protest against the government's policy of
not paying economic compensation to the damage caused by the
Katyusha rocket attacks recently. (BC-Israel-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A senior French official Sunday made a visit to
Beirut to discuss the latest development after the Israeli air
blitz on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Yves Messuziere, who heads French Foreign Ministry's Middle
East and North Africa Department, held talks with Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that Lebanon and Israel end the
strike-and-revenge formula soon and settle the problem through
the international monitoring committee.
(BC-Lebanon-France-Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The Iraqi government has decided to allow Iraqi
citizens and resident foreigners in Iraq to circulate and deposit
foreign currencies acceptable to the Iraqi Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Revolutionary Command Council, the top legislative
body, issued the decision on Saturday evening, the Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, Iraqis inside and outside Iraq and
foreigners in Iraq can open current and fixed accounts in
licensed banks and get interests with the rates decided by the
Iraqi Central Bank, said INA. (BC-Iraq-Foreign Currencies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Visiting Pakistani Minister of Kashmir Affairs Abdul
Majeed Malik said here Sunday the use of nuclear weapons will not
be adopted or even considered by Pakistan over the Kashmir crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he stopped short of directly ruling out the
possibility of a major conventional war between India and Pakistan
if Indian troops crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in the Pakistani embassy in Amman, Malik
stressed the need for a peaceful solution to the Kashmir crisis,
but said his country will not give up its rights of self-defense.
(BC-Jordan-Pakistan-Kashmir) 
</P>
</TEXT>
