<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- A Dubai customshouse report reveals that the emirate's
gold imports in the first five months of 1999 have dropped to
119.1 tons, after several years of record high.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoted in Sunday's local press, said imports during
the corresponding period of last year stood at 219.8 tons, down
from 261.7 tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Electricity and Energy Maher
Abaza has announced allocation of 470 million pounds (134 million
U.S. dollars) for the implementation of the national program for
rural electrification during the fiscal year 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's "Alam Al Yom" daily quoted Abaza as saying that the
program incorporates the establishment of 68 new transformation
plants to meet the required needs for electricity of towns and
villages.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian project for the use and transfer of
agricultural technology has set up a site on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's "Alam Al Yom" reported the project aims at improving
Egyptian exports by providing external markets with data on the
quality of Egyptian products.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is to hold a fair in Kigali, Rwanda, on July 1-5
to display handicraft and cottage industries, Egyptian Minister of
Rural Development Mahmoud Sherif said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sherif said the fair, organized by his ministry, shows his
country's desire to promote ties with Rwanda and comes out of its
keenness on opening markets in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will be the first country to stage a fair in Rwanda,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
