<HEADLINE> Zambian President Praised for DRC Peace Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Gabonese Vice-President Didjob
Divungi-Di- Dinge praised here Sunday Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba for his tireless effort for an end to the conflict in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba is doing tremendous work in trying to end the
11-month-old war, said Ndinge, who is here to attend the regional
summit on peace in DRC, which was postponed to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ndinge expressed his hope that the on-gong consultations on the
security concerns and the cease-fire agreement by officials will
quickly be finalized to pave the way for the summit, at which the
cease-fire agreement will be signed.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who was mandated by Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to mediate a peace solution to war, told the
Gabonese vice-president that the war will come to an end as a
result of the overwhelming support and commitment from SADC, the
Organization for African Unity (OAU) and all stakeholders to end
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said the conflict should quickly be resolved so that all the
 resources could be devoted to the development of DRC and the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The conflict is a big challenge to Africa and all the efforts
to try to end the war should not be motivated by personal gain but
by the need to end the suffering of displaced people, Chiluba
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
