<HEADLINE> Pakistani Official Rules out Nuclear Option Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Pakistani Minister of
Kashmir Affairs Abdul Majeed Malik said here Sunday the use of
nuclear weapons will not be adopted or even considered by Pakistan
over the Kashmir crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, he stopped short of directly ruling out the
possibility of a major conventional war between India and Pakistan
if Indian troops crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in the Pakistani embassy in Amman, Malik
stressed the need for a peaceful solution to the Kashmir crisis,
but said his country will not give up its rights of self-defense.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is currently striving to defuse the ongoing crisis and
tensions over Kashmir and to bring the Indian side to the
negotiation table, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malik was sent by Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif as a
special envoy to brief Arab countries on the current situation in
Kashmir and to explain Pakistan's position on the issue, Pakistani
embassy officials said.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing crisis between Pakistan and India started after
Indian troops launched campaigns to expel what New Delhi called
Pakistan-backed intruders into the India-held part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Troops from both sides have been exchanging fire in
Kashmir over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, Pakistan denied that it is militarily supporting those
guerrillas, saying it only gives moral support to those "freedom
fighters."
</P>
<P>
India has so far rejected Pakistan's proposals to hold talks,
saying no talks are possible before it expels all the intruders
out of its part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan, both having exploded their first nuclear
weapons last year, have fought three wars in the past half a
century, two over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Malik is also expected to meet Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein on Monday over the Kashmir issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
