<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-27 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Party Delegations Attend Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Greek Cypriot
AKEL party on Sunday crossed into the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north Cyprus to attend the 17th conference of the Republican
Turkish Party (RTP).
</P>
<P>
The three-member delegation headed by AKEL secretary-general
Dimitris Christofias went to the north to attend the conference at
the invitation of RTP leader Mehmet Ali Talat, the Cyprus News
Agency (CNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
AKEL is the main opposition left-wing party in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
An AKEL Central Committee message to the conference underlines
the need for Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots to seek common
grounds while respecting their different national backgrounds and
traditions.
</P>
<P>
The message says a future settlement to the Cyprus issue should
guarantee the independence, territorial integrity, sovereignty and
unity of a bicommunal Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot political parties have been
maintaining contacts despite efforts by Turkish Cypriot
authorities to ban meetings between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
Since December 1997, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has
not allowed Turkish Cypriots to participate in most bicommunal
events or to cross into the Greek Cypriots-controlled area in
reaction to a European Union decision to open accession talks with
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to settle the Cyprus issue have been stalled since
Denktash demanded that the international community recognizes his
break-away state in north Cyprus, now only recognized by Turkey,
before negotiations can be undertaken with the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
