<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African States Urge EU to Lift Fish Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania, Uganda and Kenya
have jointly appealed to the European Union (EU) to lift a
multi-million-dollar ban on exports of fish produced from the Lake
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The three countries, bordering the second-largest freshwater
lake, assure that illegal fishing with chemical substance has been
contained and consumers do not have to worry about food health.
</P>
<P>
Ministers responsible for fisheries from the three east African
 countries, who met in the Tanzanian capital Saturday, have said
that law enforcement organs have intensified surveillance on the
lake.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also informed that measures have been taken to
enhance people's awareness of perils in poisoning fish, media
reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, EU declared a ban on imports of fresh and frozen
fish products from the three countries following reports that
unscrupulous people had been using pesticides for cotton in
fishing activities which posed threats to food health.
</P>
<P>
The ban means that the three countries will suffer a loss of at
least 250 million U.S. dollars annually. A number of people on the
lake have lost jobs and fish prices have nosedived after the trade
embargo.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the ministers agreed to co-ordinating in
improving sanitary standards in fish processing facilities and the
quality of fish products from the lake.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Gets Less HIV-tainted Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of HIV-infected
blood donors has decreased because of better targeting, the
National Blood Transfusion Service of Zimbabwe (NBTS) has said.
</P>
<P>
NBTS information, research and public relations manager Rodwell
Shamhu told the Zimbabwe News Agency Sunday that the rate of HIV
positive blood donors had declined from 1.16 percent in 1996/97 to
0.89 percent in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
"The major factors contributing to this trend are better
targeting of donors and improved donor selection techniques," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the general awareness of the blood donation
requirements had also reduced the number of HIV-positive donors.
</P>
<P>
There was also use of on-going research work, he said, which
provided indicators for implementing donor recruitment, selection
and retention strategies.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of 1999, NBTS had realized increased
blood collections of nine percent compared with last year.
</P>
