<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Prime Minister Leaves for Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAHORE, Pakistan, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif left here Sunday night for a five-day official visit
to China, the second since he assumed premiership in February
1997.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said in his departure statement that during his stay in
Beijing, he will hold bilateral talks with his Chinese counterpart
Zhu Rongji, call on Chinese President Jiang Zemin and meet with Li
Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The visit is in the tradition of frequent high-level exchanges
between Pakistan and China which allow a regular review on matters
of mutual interest leading to a further strengthening of the
"excellent existing relations" between the two countries, said
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister said he will brief the Chinese
side on the latest developments in Kashmir and underscore the
urgency for a just and final settlement of the Kashmir dispute in
the interest of peace and stability in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sharif described the Pakistan-China friendship as "a model of
inter-state relations." "It is a relationship based on principles
of peaceful co-existence which have stood the test of time and
changing global trends."
</P>
<P>
"We continue to share a close identity of perceptions on major
regional and international issues," said Sharif, adding that
"Pakistan feels honored to have China as its close friend and
ally."
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed his thanks for China's consistent and generous
assistance and support extended to Pakistan over the years.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke highly of the progress China has made during the
past decade, and said that a strong and prosperous China is "a
source of strength for its friends and a powerful factor for peace
and stability in the region and the world at large."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is determined to join hands with China, said Sharif.
He expressed the belief that the relationship between Pakistan and
China will reach new heights in the new century for the
development and prosperity of the two peoples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
