<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, U.S. Officials Meet Over Kargil Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Deputy Assistant
Secretary of State Gibson Lanpher Sunday night met the Indian
prime minister's Principal Secretary Brajesh Mishra and External
Affairs Ministry officials, and they discussed the latest
situation in Kargil sector of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
No details were disclosed about the meetings. But an Indian
spokesman said the talks between the two delegations lasted for
about two hours.
</P>
<P>
Lanpher briefed the Indian side about the discussions held by
General Anthony Zinni of the U.S. Central Command chief with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Army Chief of Staff
General Parvez Musharraf in Islamabad earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Embassy spokesperson also said here Saturday that
Lanpher had come just on a mission to brief Indian officials on
the U.S. team's talks in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman said in a statement said "It is imperative
that Pakistan heed the advice of the international community and
take immediate steps to withdraw the armed intruders from the
Indian side of the Line of Control."
</P>
<P>
"Once the armed intruders are withdrawn, it is possible to take
steps to resume the composite dialogue process that responds to
the wishes of the people of both India and Pakistan to live in
peace and amity," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Lanpher told newsmen here after his meetings with Indian
officials: "I have brought no proposals on safe passage or
anything else from Islamabad."
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, The U.S. and Pakistan in their
talks Friday had made a deal to allow infiltrators holed up in
Kargil to withdraw quietly from Indian territory. India agreed to
the idea in principle.
</P>
<P>
An Indian External Affairs Ministry spokesman told newsmen here
Friday that no proposal on providing the infiltrators with an
"exit corridor" had been received and that they would have to find
their way back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
