<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Lifts Ban on Circulation, Deposit of Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi government has decided
to allow Iraqi citizens and resident foreigners in Iraq to
circulate and deposit foreign currencies acceptable to the Iraqi
Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Revolutionary Command Council, the top legislative
body, issued the decision on Saturday evening, the Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision, Iraqis inside and outside Iraq and
foreigners in Iraq can open current and fixed accounts in
licensed banks and get interests with the rates decided by the
Iraqi Central Bank, said INA.
</P>
<P>
In the past, neither Iraqis nor foreigners in Iraq were allowed
to deposit foreign currencies in Iraqi banks. They had to exchange
their foreign currencies into Iraqi dinars, the Iraqi currency,
for deposit or circulation.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the measure is aimed at attracting
deposit in foreign currencies and stablizing the Iraqi dinar, which
is rated at over 2,000 against one U.S. dollar in black markets in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Before the United Nations clamped economic sanctions on Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, one Iraqi dinar is worth
3.3 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
