<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Deal for S. Leone to Be Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A peace agreement between the Sierra
Leonean government and the rebels would be announced after the
rebels explain the agreement to its commanders in the bush, said
reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) has been seeking a
power- sharing arrangement in a government of national unity
during the month-long peace talks being held between the
government and the rebels in Togolese capital of Lome.
</P>
<P>
The talks had been deadlocked over the number of cabinet
positions being offered by the government to the rebels and
mediators at the talks are believed to convince the government to
increase the offer from three to eight ministerial posts -- four
cabinet posts and four lower posts.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the mediators said that the RUF led by Foday
Sankoh had accepted the latest offer by President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh who attended talks late Friday with Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo told reporters earlier that "I think we have
come to the end of the negotiations, it is just a matter of
getting a mandate from my people."
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough of the peace talks seems to have been helped
by the involvement of Obasanjo who had long discussions with the
government and RUF representatives.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian president undertook a shuttle visit to Sierra
Leone, Liberia and Togo last Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo and Togolese President Gnassingbe Eyadema, who is the
current chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), met both sides late on Friday in Eyadema's home village
of Kara.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, a joint statement released Saturday
urged the two sides of the eight-year conflicts in Sierra Leone to
make "a final effort for peace and reconciliation". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
