<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt Urged to Privatize Petroleum Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi business leader Sunday
urged the government to privatize the state-owned Bangladesh
Petroleum Corporation (BPC) to protect consumers' interests, the
national news agency BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
"The government should privatize the BPC to stop irregularities
and allow the organization to serve the consumers' interest more
effectively," Abdul Awal Mintoo, president of the Bangladesh
Chambers of Commerce and Industries, told a seminar on problems of
fuel in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Privatization of the BPC would ensure accountability,
transparency and productivity, which in turn would safeguard the
interest of the consumers of the country's sole fuel dealing
authority, he said.
</P>
<P>
The fuel refining cost might be brought down to three percent
from existing 12 percent if accountability and transparency was
ensured in the BPC through privatization, he added.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Fuel Owners' Association also underlined the
need for inclusion of people's representatives in the BPC's
management to help stop adulteration of petrol with kerosene.
</P>
<P>
About 800 petrol pumps are in operation in the country while
scores of others are being put up. Some 98 percent of the
country's fuel needs are being imported by the government while
the rest comes from local gas fields.
</P>
<P>
There are about 15 fuel depots in the country and the number is
inadequate and needs to be doubled, said participants at the
seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
