<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Greek Dictator Papadopoulos Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Greece's former dictator George
Papadopoulos, who led a military junta from 1967 to 1973, died in
an Athens hospital on Sunday at the age of 80.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1919, Papadopoulos was an army colonel when he seized
power in an April 1967 coup.
</P>
<P>
In December 1967, Papadopoulos took over as Prime Minister and
Defense Minister, and in 1973, he became President of Greece.
</P>
<P>
With the return of democratic rule to Greece in 1974, he was
arrested and sentenced to death for treason, but the government
led by Constantine Karamanlis commuted the sentence to life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Papadopoulos was jailed in the Korydallos Prison but in August
1996, he was transferred to hospital for health reasons and
remained there under police guard until his death on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Advance into Quarterfinals as Group B Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil scored the equalizer four
minutes into injury time to hold Germany to a 3-3 draw and qualified for
the quarterfinals as Group B leaders here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In one of the most entertaining game of the World Cup, the
Brazilian team, which have already booked a berth in the top eight
with two straight wins over Mexico and Italy, fell 1-0 behind at the
8th minute when Birgit Prinz opened the scoring for the German team.
</P>
<P>
But the Brazilians, regarded as the most exciting and
entertaining team in the tournament, answered quickly with an
equalizer through Katia Da Silva at the 15th minute.
</P>
<P>
Top Brazilian forward Sissi, who tied with Sun Wen of China with 5
goals to lead the scorers' list, sent a curved free-kick into the net
five minutes later to put Brazil 2-1 ahead.
</P>
<P>
It seemed the German team would lose the game and give Italy a
chance to overtake if the Italians could score a big-margin win over
Mexico later on Sunday, but the Germans just would not give up their
hopes.
</P>
<P>
The German girls showed their determination and made full use of
their physical advantage in the second half, levelled the score 2-2
only one minute into the second half.
</P>
<P>
Birgit Prinz charged into the Brazilian area and was fouled down
by defender Suzana. The South Korean referee Im Eun Ju
awarded a penalty to the German team and Bettina Wiegmann made no
mistake from the spot.
</P>
<P>
The German team played better after the goal and dominated the
midfield. They again took over the lead at the 58th minute when
defender Ann Jones Stephanie slotted homefrom close range.
</P>
<P>
The Germans had more chances of scoring and as the game heading
to the end, it seemed they could win the game and qualify for the
quarterfinals as the group leaders.
</P>
<P>
But the Brazilian team scored a dramatic goal four minutes into
the injury time when Maicon collected a rebound within the penalty
area and sent it home with a right-footer.
</P>
<P>
Maicon had entered the match as a second-half substitute when
Brazil fell behind and needed a goal to tie the game and win the
group.
</P>
<P>
The win enables Brazil qualify as the group winners with 7
points. The Germans also qualify for the top eight with 5 points
from one win and two draws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
