<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges Strategy for Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said here on Monday that the Russian leadership needs to develop a
strategy for the whole of Yugoslavia including Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He made this comment at the start of his meeting with Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
"With your help Russia has waged an excellent campaign in
Kosovo and the whole of Yugoslavia," he told Sergeyev.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he was glad to see that Sergeyev is optimistic
about the success of the peacekeeping operation, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The president said he is concerned about the details of the
Russian peacekeeping operation in Kosovo, noting that all
decisions on the operation should be made collectively.
</P>
<P>
The Pristina airport has great strategic importance and Russia
will operate the airport jointly with peacekeepers from other
countries and is prepared to help them if needed, he added.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Russian troops arrived at the Slatina airport near
Pristina on June 11 to NATO's surprise, strengthening Moscow's
hand in negotiating a deal on Russia's peacekeeping role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
No details are available for the Yeltsin-Sergeyev closed-door
meeting, which Yeltsin said focused on Russia's peacekeeping
mission in Kosovo and the whole of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Several Russian transport planes carrying technical equipment
and military personnel have landed at the Slatina airport since
last Saturday. Three NATO aircraft carrying similar supplies are
expected to arrive at Pristina on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Then the airport, badly damaged in NATO's 11-week bombing
campaign, will be closed for four days, during which Russian and
NATO engineers will outfit the airport for operation to meet
international standards. The airport is expected to open to normal
flights on July 1, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
