<HEADLINE> France Minimizes Dispute With Israel Over Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- France tuned down on Monday its
dispute with Israel over Lebanon, after outgoing Israeli Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon slammed France for criticizing Israel's air
raids against Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
Both Israel's new prime minister Ehud Barak and Sharon Monday
refused to meet with the French government envoy on Middle East,
Yves Aubin de la Messuziere, who carried a letter from the French
government to Barak.
</P>
<P>
Sharon accused France of being biased when commenting on the
Israeli-Lebanese tension. He also criticized France for sending
its envoy without pre-consultation.
</P>
<P>
But French diplomats said that besides Lebanon, the purpose of
the visit by de la Messuziere to Tel Aviv is to seek the
possibility of re-launching the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"This visit was made in the wake of the Group of Eight (G-8)
summit in Cologne on June 20, during which the leaders of G-8
countries welcomed the encouraging declarations made by Mr. Barak
(on the peace process)," Agence France-Presse quoted an
unidentified French diplomat as saying in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said that France wishes to encourage Barak in pursuing the
way of peace and it also intends to play a role in helping realize
peace between Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Eight people were killed and 60 injured in the air raids by
Israeli warplanes against Lebanon last Thursday and Friday. Israel
said it was taking revenge for the rocket attacks by Shiite Muslim
Hezbollah guerrillas upon northern Israel, which killed two
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
France has called on Israel and Hezbollah guerrillas to stop
taking actions of reprisal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
