<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia Monday signed a Record
of Discussion with five countries on the extension of the
tripartite cooperation project between Japan-ASEAN-Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony held at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
was attended by Cambodia's rural development minister, secretary
of state of foreign affairs and ambassadors of Japan, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The record is the extension of the duration of the joint
cooperation for the rural development and resettlement project in
Cambodia, commonly known as "The Tripartite Cooperation Project
between Japan-ASEAN-Cambodia."
</P>
<P>
The project, which was worth about 11.63 million U.S. dollars,
would be undertaken from September 30, 1993 to the end of June
1999.
</P>
<P>
The extension of the duration of the project until March 31,
2000 will be implemented at an estimated cost of 1 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the project, according to a statement released by
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, "is to encourage rural development
and resettlement of the returnees, internally displaced persons,
demobilized military personnel and the local population, as well
as to introduce appropriate techniques of agriculture and income
generating activities." 
