<HEADLINE> Law on Troops in Macao Special Administrative Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Law on Stationing Troops in
the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) was approved by the
10th meeting of the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, the chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, said after
the law passed that it embodies the basic principle of "one
country, two systems." He also said the law meets the Central
Government's need to effectively handle the defense issue in Macao
and conforms with Macao's real conditions. The law will play a
significant role in ensuring that troops stationed in Macao
perform their duties according to law and safeguard state
sovereignty, unity, reunification, territorial integrity and the
safety of Macao, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Law has 30 articles in 6 sections on general principles,
the duties of the troops, the relationship between the troops and
the Macao SAR government, the discipline of military personnel and
their jurisdiction, and supplementary provisions.
</P>
<P>
The Law will take effect on December 20, when China resumes the
exercise of sovereignty over Macao. According to the Basic Law of
the Macao SAR, the Central Government will be responsible for
defense matters in Macao.
</P>
<P>
At the 3rd plenary session of the Preparatory Committee of the
Macao SAR held on September 18, 1998, Vice-Premier and Chairman of
the Preparatory Committee Qian Qichen announced on behalf of the
Central Government that it will station troops in Macao on
December 20.
</P>
<P>
A proposal on the Law on Stationing Troops in Macao, that was
submitted to the NPC Standing Committee by the State Council and
the Central Military Commission (CMC), said that under the
guidance of the basic principle of "one country, two systems" and
on the basis of the Constitution and the Basic Law of the Macao
SAR and in accordance with the duties of the troops to be
stationed in Macao, the Law on Stationing Troops in the Macao SAR
has been drafted after a long period of study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
