<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Protests French Stand on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel on Monday staged a
protest against France's stand on Israel's recent air raids
against Lebanon, saying it is "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
David Granit, the acting deputy director general for western
Europe in Israeli foreign ministry, delivered the protest to
French envoy Yves Aubin de la Messuzires, who arrived here earlier
in the day for a short visit.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Granit also passed to the French envoy a
letter from Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon to his French
counterpart Hubert Vedrine, in which Sharon said the French
statement regarding the Israeli assault is "unbalanced."
</P>
<P>
Israel will "do whatever it feels is necessary to do" to protect
its security, said the hard-line Israeli minister in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Israel launched air attacks on Lebanese civilian targets on
Wednesday and Thursday, killing at least eight civilians and
wounding over 60 others.
</P>
<P>
The attacks were said to have been carried out in retaliation
for earlier Lebanese guerrilla attacks which killed two Israeli
civilians in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Thursday's air strikes, the French government
issued a statement criticizing Israel for the attacks, but failed
to blame the Lebanese Hezbollah for its Katyusha attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
The statement also announced that France is dispatching two
diplomats to Syria, Lebanon, Israel and the Palestinian territory
to defuse the tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Messuzires is also carrying a letter from French President
Jacques Chirac to Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, calling
on him to take immediate measures to push the Mideast peace
process ahead.
</P>
<P>
But due to the French statement, Barak refused to meet with the
French envoy and decided to accept the letter through a third
party.
</P>
<P>
Sharon and other Israeli government leaders all refused to meet
the French envoy.
</P>
<P>
French officials here said they are sorry "if there has been
any misunderstanding, and hope the visit of the diplomats will
contribute to calming the situation and advancing the peace
process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
