<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Differences Appear in Congo (K) Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, Zimbabwe and Congo (K) have
 disagreed on the modalities of disarming the militiamen fighting
in eastern Congo at the ministerial meeting in Zambian capital
Lusaka Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting disclosed that the three countries said
they cannot sign a cease-fire agreement without a proper mechanism
being put in place on disarming armed groups in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
They explained that the three countries want to know exactly
how this will be done before committing themselves to the signing
of the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
And Zimbabwe Foreign Minister Sten Mudenge said his government
was happy with the first document that was done in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that a number of issues are to be resolved in
the new document before the cease-fire can be signed formally.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was adjourned to later in the afternoon to give the
 delegates time to consult.
</P>
<P>
Officials involved in the Congo peace talks on Sunday night
finalized the cease-fire document which will accommodate fresh
proposals from Uganda and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, Amama Mbabazi
confirmed that Uganda had come up with fresh ideas after looking
at the paper prepared by the secretariat which earlier gathered
views from all belligerent countries and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi said Uganda felt the previous paper did not address all
the issues, hence the need to refine it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African Foreign Minister Nkhsazana Zuma told
reporters she was hopeful the cease-fire would be signed as
officials had been discussing modalities of its implementation.
</P>
<P>
"Of course the various officials stuck to their points but a
lot of progress has been made," she said.
</P>
<P>
Congolese Foreign Minister Abdulayi Yerodia expressed optimism
that a final solution would be found to the conflict as he said
much progress had been made.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by ministers from Zambia, Kenya,
Uganda, Rwanda, Zimbabwe, Namibia, Tanzania and the DRC.
</P>
<P>
If the ministers approved the document, the heads of state
would meet in Zambia to endorse the signature of the agreement,
observers here say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
