<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Australia's Tax Reform Poises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new tax, which will come into force on July 1 next year,
could largely make the economy more efficient and competitive,
they said.
</P>
<P>
"GST has little to do with tax," said Steve Corbett, national
GST program director for Touche Tohmatsu. "It's about the
transaction, systems and processes you put in place to manage it."
</P>
<P>
With the GST changing the ways of cash flows in different
businesses, small businesses, especially retailers, are the
largest beneficiaries of the reform, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
While firms turning over more than 20 million Australian
dollars (13.2 million U.S. dollars) a year have up to 30 days to
make their GST payments, businesses under 20 million Australian
dollars can choose between monthly or quarterly GST returns.
</P>
<P>
The small businesses collect a 10 percent GST on nearly all
their sales, except basic food, yet in most cases they won't pay
GST on goods purchased for at least 30 days.
</P>
<P>
This could encourage the small businesses to flourish, the
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The GST system will also have impact on competitive strategies,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Until today, aggressive businesses chasing market share have
often resorted to extending favorable terms, up to 180 days, in
order to win new contracts.
</P>
<P>
However, anyone who tries to adopt such a strategy under the
GST regime will need a good bank manager. The capital cost of such
competitive strategy rises appreciably under the GST system.
</P>
<P>
Learning how to live with GST system involves a detailed
knowledge of business and finance systems and processes, the
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Those that don't understand the cash-flow mechanics of their
businesses could be squeezed at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
"Understanding cash flow on both ends, input and output, are
critical if you aren't going to get in trouble," Gorbett said.
</P>
<P>
While small businesses like retailers get the sweet end of the
GST pineapple, some groups, notably importers and manufacturers,
get the rough end of it, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
An importer must pay GST on imported goods once they clear
customs but the GST receipts from sales that offset the GST cost
on imports could be months away.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the importer is actually lending money
interest-free to the tax collector.
</P>
<P>
It's a not too dissimilar situation for manufacturers, although
the predicament will vary substantially from firm to firm, the
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Some manufacturers with long production cycles, who buy inputs
many months before selling finished goods, could need up to 10
percent more working capital under the GST system.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, manufacturers with short production cycles,
billing ever couple of weeks, won't have the same capital problem.
</P>
<P>
Under this impact, manufacturers would learn which parts of
their businesses made profits and which did not, the analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the investment side, the GST is likely to have
limited impact on personal investors, but the broader tax reform
that comes with it will introduce a series of changes that will
affect investment strategies, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest impacts to be felt by personal investors
from the GST will be an increase in the fees and expenses charged
by stockbrokers, financial advisers, managed funds and financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Investment classes such as property, insurance and collectibles
will also be hit by specific changes that could alter the way
retail investors manage their portfolios, they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a well-documented potential rise in banking
charges, other financial services could increase in cost under the
new tax regime.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the GST, a fee charged for placing an
investment does not attract the 10 percent tax, but
fee-for-service advice for a financial adviser does.
</P>
<P>
Accountants and lawyers charging a fixed hourly rate for advice
will also have to add the GST to a client's bill.
</P>
<P>
At the bottom of the impact list, the Australian Taxation
Office (ATO) faces severe pressure to implement the new tax system
due to a 1-billion-Australian dollar (660 million U.S. dollars)
shortfall for the GST administration, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Michael Dirkis, tax director at the Taxation Institute of
Australia and a former ATO official, said the tax office would be
short of resource when the GST comes into effect on July 1 next
year.
</P>
<P>
The country's business would pay the price and the tax office
would be forced to rely on "shock treatment" to raise revenue, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The tax office would be unable to advise business properly on
how to comply with the GST, instead relying on random audits that
were based on making businesses prove they were not tax cheats, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The funding crisis is confirmed by the tax office's recent
attempt to grab some of the 500 million Australian dollars (330
million U.S. dollars) in funding for GST compliance costs for
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
This proved that the tax office was "desperate" for resources
to implement the GST, Dirkis said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radioactive Leak Reported in Russian Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Two Russian workers suffered
exposure to high doses of radiation two weeks ago in a chemical
plant in the central part of the country, Russian Atomic Energy
Minister Yevgeny Adamov said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the failure of the emergency prevention system
rather than any human error for the radioactive leak in the
Siberian Chemical Plant in Seversk, Tomsk region, on June 14, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Adamov, who is attending a meeting in Obninsk, Kaluga to mark
the 45th anniversary of the launch of the world's first nuclear
power plant, said that the managers of the plant in Seversk had
done their best to prevent emergencies, but the prevention system
failed to work properly.
</P>
<P>
The accident was originally attributed to a human error
committed in repairing a reactor.
</P>
<P>
Radiation was kept inside the hall that houses the reactor, in
the wake of the occurrence of the emergency rated level 2 on the 0-
7 level scale. Level 7, the worst level, applies to the Chernobyl
disaster, Adamov said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said a crisis center would be set up in Moscow in
September to monitor the daily operation and safety of the country
's nuclear power stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
