<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriots Reject Confederate Solution on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' government said Monday
it will not discuss a confederate solution to the Cyprus issue,
threatening not to participate in talks with the Turkish side if
such a solution is set as a precondition.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Costas Serezis said the Greek Cypriot
government remains committed to the U.N. resolutions which
stipulate for the setting up of a bizonal, bicommunal federation
in the island.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that President Glafcos Clerides will decide
on how to react if the issue comes up at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is expected to approve two
resolutions, one on the U.N. Secretary-General's good offices
mission and the other on the six-month extension of the mandate of
the U.N. peace-keeping force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to settle the Cyprus issue have been stalled since the
Turkish Cypriots demanded that the world community recognizes
their break-away state in northern Cyprus, now only recognized by
Turkey, before negotiations can be undertaken with the Greek
Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
