<HEADLINE> Chinese Getting Into Computer Music (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The new computer technology now
means that a guitarist can make music without an instrument and
Josef Fung, the president of the International Computer Music
Conference (ICMC), is organizing a computer music festival in
October in Beijing that demonstrates this new fact of life.
</P>
<P>
There, a guitarist, with sensors pasted on his body, can move
his body and create music, and a group of engineers can climb up
on a giant "sensor-net", a scaffold-like structure with sensor
rods linked to computers, to jointly create different melodies.
</P>
<P>
Fung, who is an Icelandic-Chinese, described this avant-garde
music to a Xinhua reporter in his studio where he manipulated a PC
to produce strange sounds and explained: "The sounds we are
hearing include those from the natural environment as well as
those that might never be heard by people."
</P>
<P>
The computer music system consists of a PC, a synthesizer, a
sensor, and other electronic equipment and can use a lot of
software. "Human beings can hear sound in a frequency range
between 20 and 20,000 hertz, but traditional musical instruments
can only produce a limited range," Fung says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Getting into Computer Music (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A musician will produce different music in different
performances, Fung says, letting his mind wander and create music
randomly.
</P>
<P>
For the proposed computer festival in October, Fung plans to
show traditional Chinese martial arts in a high-tech way with
performers covered by a light circle, inside which their moves
will be digitally read by a powerful computer on the spot, and
that, the 44-year-old musician says, must be tremendously exciting.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Fung was a member of a panel of judges for an
international computer music festival in Hong Kong and led a group
of famous Chinese musicians in a key-note performance.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, the ICMC became a sort of musical Olympics and more
than 1,000 composers, musicians, professors, and engineers from 36
countries have joined it. This year it decided to stage the annual
festival in a developing country for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts here say that computer music will open up the
minds of the Chinese people and push software production.
</P>
</TEXT>
