<HEADLINE> U.S.-ASEAN Business Council Gives Thumbs-up to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is making good
progress in its efforts to respond to the financial turmoil in
Asia, President of the U.S.-ASEAN Business Council Ernest Z. Bower
has said.
</P>
<P>
Bower said the response to the crisis in Malaysia has shown
measurable results.
</P>
<P>
"There is a vocal commitment among the country's (Malaysia)
leadership to consider the viewpoints of the business community
regarding what the next steps in the reform process ought to be,"
he was quoted as saying in a statement released by the National
Economic Action Council (NEAC) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bower also said the bank and corporate restructuring are well
underway in Malaysia, adding that the country has a relatively
strong banking system in which 16 out of 40 commercial banks are
foreign owned.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest banking directory, 14 out of 37
locally incorporated commercial banks in the country are foreign
owned.
</P>
<P>
"American business supported Malaysia's economic transformation
and continues to do so," he said, adding that Malaysia is the
second largest importer per capita for U.S. goods and services.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S. business community is looking forward
to continuing consultations with Malaysian business leaders and
policy-makers, and is hoping to expand discussions on policies and
their implementation in both countries which will affect bilateral
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Bower said his recent visit to Malaysia was aimed at
continuing the "long-standing work to build Malaysian-American
trade and investment ties and gaining a better understanding of
the current economic and business trends in Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
"We are eager to build upon the strong foundations of the
long-standing relationship with Malaysia and are seeking
partnership in concrete efforts to drive forward the growth and
prosperity of both economies," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-ASEAN Business Council is the largest national
organization representing American businesses interested in
Malaysia and the other member countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
He said the council is not alone in its assessment as more
international organizations have projected growth for Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"It demonstrates that Malaysia's economic managers are soundly
in charge of the situation and that their policies for dealing
with the crisis are appropriate for the nation (Malaysia)," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
