<HEADLINE> Russia Has Only Limited Contacts With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Russia's contacts with NATO now are
only those needed "for joint participation in the peacekeeping
operation" in Kosovo, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Broader contacts with NATO, which were suspended following the
U.S.-led military alliance launched air strikes on Yugoslavia on
March 24, will have to be negotiated, Ivanov told a news
conference following his talks with Kazakh Deputy Prime Minister
and Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart Tokayev.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Leonid Ivashov, director of the Russian
Defense Ministry's International Military Cooperation Department,
said the visit of a Russian military delegation to NATO
headquarters does not imply that Russia intends to restore its
relations with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
A delegation headed by Vice Adm. Valentin Kuznetsov, head of
the ministry's International Law Board, will discuss with the
NATO command only issues related to the peacekeeping operation in
Kosovo, the Interfax news agency quoted Ivashov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation will discuss at NATO headquarters and at the
South European command those issues concerning Russia's
representation in these bodies, as far as the peacekeeping mission
is concerned, as well as joint command at the peacekeepers'
headquarters in Pristina," capital city of the Yugoslav province
of Kosovo, Ivashov said.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal hammered out between Russia and the United States,
Russia will dispatch 3,600 peacekeepers in Kosovo along with NATO
troops.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be back in Moscow on Thursday, Ivashov
said. 
</P>
