<HEADLINE> China Raising Standards for IT Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China is to learn how to use
technical standards as a means of reducing the amount of reckless
competition from foreign companies in its information technology
business and protecting the interests of Chinese companies,
according to Vice-Minister of the Information Industry Lu Xinkui.
</P>
<P>
Lu told a ministry conference on standardization here today
that the time of just copying international standards is no more.
Since IT standards involve patents, he said, it will be more
negative than positive to just adopt foreign standards.
</P>
<P>
If China adopts other country's standards on video discs, it
will pay several hundred million U.S. dollars for the rights in
the next few years, he explained, and if a country refuses to sell
the IT rights to China, then China's products will be shut off
from the world while foreign products will penetrate the Chinese
market without opposition.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has to learn from other countries about
using technical standards as a method other than trade barriers to
protect its IT industry from competition from multinationals, so
China will try to establish a framework of standards that meets
the development needs of its IT industry in the next two to three
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
