<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Concerns Over Growing Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
here Monday expressed concern over the narcotics business which
has not been affected by monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The opium business, which continues to attack the younger
generation, has not been affected, although the country is facing
several economic and political problems," Habibie said during the
commemoration of World Anti-Opium Day held at the state palace.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the trade of such banned substances continues,
the nation should start striking the "drums of war" to combat it,
otherwise the fruits of development will be useless.
</P>
<P>
Habibie also said that criminal operation in drug production
and trafficking has become ruthless, sophisticated and
well-organized.
</P>
<P>
"Through a forum, I instructed the security forces and law
enforcers to carry out the policies against narcotics criminals to
the best of their ability, according to the law," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on law experts to carry out studies whether or
not the laws are adequate in eradicating drug criminality.
</P>
<P>
As a country consisting of thousands of islands, Indonesia is
being seen by national as well as foreign anti-drug agencies as a
potential transit point for international drug syndicate.
</P>
<P>
An official said earlier that the number of drug addicts in
Indonesia was 0.062 percent of its total population of 202
million. This was a relative low figure compared to other
countries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
