<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Would-be Ministers Signs Ethics Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The 42 would-be ministers and 12
presidential advisers Sunday signed on a 14-point code of conduct,
enshrining probity, transparency and accountability in governance,
The Guardian paper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new ethics code is aimed at instilling confidence and trust
in public office holders - both for the current crop of officials
and for the successors in office as ministers and special
advisers, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The document declared that the government officials should be
open to scrutiny by members of the public and "open and
transparent in the discharge of public duties."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, who is expected to
swear-in the new appointees Wednesday, described the document as a
landmark achievement in the history of governance in the most
populous African country.
</P>
<P>
"The adoption of the code of conduct for ministers and special
advisers in the federation is a landmark in the revival of just
and honest government in Nigeria," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo told the would-be ministers in capital Abuja Saturday
that "you must be prepared to make sacrifice, if any sacrifice for
this purpose is considered too much, it would be better not to
accept the responsibility."
</P>
<P>
The president last Wednesday submitted his first bill, an anti-
corruption bill, to the National Assembly, or parliament of this
west African country.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo's latest moves are clearly aimed at stepping up the
anti- corruption thrust, which he promised would be one of his
government's top priorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
