<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Calls for More Attention on AIDS Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. agency on AIDS has urged the
international community to pay more attention to the fight against
the fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
"We must keep on building this momentum and turn it into new
resources and sustained energy to fight the epidemic," Peter Piot,
executive director of the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS
(UNAIDS), said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Public acknowledgment of the urgency of AIDS is the first step
" and "every part of society must be involved in responding to the
epidemic," Piot told the opening session of the eighth meeting of
UNAIDS' governing body, the Program Coordinating Board.
</P>
<P>
Piot stressed that the expanded response requires a long-term
commitment of human and financial resources, which has so far been
lacking in many countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent report sponsored by UNAIDS, after a quick
influx of donor spending in the late 1980s, support for the
international fight against AIDS began to level off in 1990, with
wealthy nations allocating an average of less than 1 percent of
their annual official development assistance (ODA) budgets for
AIDS programs in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, 33.4 million people were living with HIV
infection or AIDS, and a further 13.9 million had already died
from AIDS-related causes since the start of the epidemic,
according to estimates by UNAIDS and the World Health Organization.
AIDS is now the leading cause of death in sub-Saharan Africa, and
the fourth leading cause of death in the world.
</P>
<P>
Piot said, "Africa can barely begin to meet its immediate and
long-term AIDS needs. Just as the continent's leaders are stepping
up their political momentum, the international community must step
up its commitment to a new partnership against AIDS in Africa."
</P>
<P>
He said UNAIDS' priority areas in the coming year will be the
young people, community-based care activities, vaccine development,
prevention of mother-to-child HIV transmission and highly
vulnerable populations.
</P>
<P>
Present at the two-day meeting are representatives from 22
governments, the seven cosponsor organizations of UNAIDS, five non-
governmental organizations and associations of people living with
HIV/AIDS, as well as some 60 governmental and non-governmental
observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
