<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices tumbled on
Singapore Stock Market Monday on profit-taking amid expectation
for a hike in U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) sank 14.98 points to
close at 2,163.66 in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
Total volume was 1,926.56 million shares valued at 1,868.03
million Singapore dollars (about 1,096.33 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers led losers by 181 to 158 with 107 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
IPC continued to top the volume list as it registered a
turnover of 165.75 million shares. It was followed by I-One.Net
that had 116.65 million units done. SMB Utd was the next with
88.77 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
IntFactor was the biggest gainer of the day gaining 31 cents to
close at 1.33 Singapore dollars. ICS picked up 28 cents to finish
at 3.58 Singapore dollars. DBS, KepCorp and SIA F moved up 20
cents each and ended at 17.20, 5.95 and 16.60 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH 100 was the biggest loser of the day,
incurring a loss of 100 cents to close at 28.80 Singapore dollars.
SPH plunged by 80 cents to finish at 29.00 Singapore dollars. OCBC
F lost 40 cents to finish at 14.30 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said small-capitalized stocks continued to take central
stage as players engaged in speculative trading.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the rise of DBS stocks to an announcement on
Saturday that it would form a new holding company to be known as
DBS Group Holdings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
