<HEADLINE> Australia Poised for New Tax System in Year 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia is poised for a new tax
system in the new millennium after the Senate gave its final
go-ahead to the 10 percent goods and services tax (GST) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The federal government declared it a great day for Australia
after the core provisions of the GST passed the Senate 38 votes to
30.
</P>
<P>
The legislation must now go back before the House of
Representatives by Wednesday for rubber-stamping before the GST
officially becomes law, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats Party deputy leader Natasha Stott Despoja
and her colleague Andrew Bartlett crossed the floor to vote
against the GST.
</P>
<P>
Independents Brian Harradine and Mal Colston also voted against
the new tax, which will be introduced from July 1, 2000, along
with Labor and the Greens.
</P>
<P>
After the vote, Australian Prime Minister John Howard said this
was a great moment for the country's economic security.
</P>
<P>
After quarter of a century of trying, Australia was finally on
the brink of tax reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
"For 25 years political parties and prime ministers and
opposition leaders have striven for this day and at long last it's
within reach," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has initially passed laws to introduce the GST and
to provide 12 billion Australian dollars (7.9 billion U.S.
dollars) in income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a second vote the upper house gave the nod to
more than 20 other GST provisions, including the contentious wine
equalization tax and compensation measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
