<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate President Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President Marcelo
Fernan resigned Monday due to his long-time illness, the senator's
office announced.
</P>
<P>
The 72-year-old former supreme court chief justice was elected
Senate President last year. He is now in hospital awaiting hip
surgery.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada expressed sadness over
Fernan's resignation, citing the lawmaker's leadership for the
passage of measures that benefited the country.
</P>
<P>
"I note with sadness the announcement of Senator Marcelo Fernan
that he has resigned as Senate President," Estrada said in a
statement read for him by Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican.
</P>
<P>
According to the country's law, Senate President is second in
line to the presidency should the country's President or Vice
President be unable to lead the country due to illness or death.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is to elect a new president when it resumes regular
sessions on July 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
