<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt saw a fiscal deficit of 1.43 billion Egyptian
pounds (420 million U.S. dollars) in the second quarter of the
current fiscal year, accounting for 0.5 percent of the country's
gross domestic product (GDP), the economic newspaper Alam Al Yom
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the period, total expenditures stood at 17.324 billion
pounds (5.095 billion dollars), whereas, revenues did not exceed
15.894 billion pounds (4.67 billion dollars), the newspaper quoted
a report by the Ministry of Economy as saying.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, fiscal deficit of the first quarter stood at 2.6
billion pounds (about 765 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The average Saudi crude oil price is expected to
exceed 13 U.S. dollars per barrel this year, which will prompt an
economic growth rate of 1.4 percent in Saudi Arabia and cut budget
deficit by some 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's gross domestic product (GDP) will rise in nominal
value this year to about 490 billion Saudi rials (about 130.7
billion dollars) as compared to 488 billion rials (about 130.1
billion dollars) last year, the Arab daily Al Hayat Monday quoted
a Saudi official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The growth was attributed to the expected rise in oil prices
and an expansion in government expenditure, said Saeed Al Sheikh,
director of the Economic Department of the Saudi Commercial
National Bank.
</P>
<P>
Saudi oil revenues will exceed 30 billion dollars this year as
compared to about 26 billion dollars last year, indicating that
the oil sector in Saudi Arabia would grow by over 15 percent in
1999, based on an average crude oil price of 13 dollars per barrel
against last year's 12 dollars, said the banking official.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq, suffering from acute shortage of hard
currency, has issued new regulations which allow Iraqi citizens
and foreigners to open bank accounts and trade in foreign
currencies, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A decree, recently approved by the Iraqi Revolutionary Command
Council and signed by President Saddam Hussein, states that Iraqis
are free to own, open bank accounts and trade in foreign
currencies as authorized by the Central Bank of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqis, living abroad while holding hard currency accounts in
Iraq, may now transfer their money abroad after producing relevant
official documents.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank will fix the interest rates on hard currency
deposits.
</P>
<P>
The current exchange rate of the U.S. dollar and Iraqi dinar
is 1:1,900, whereas, the petroleum-backed Iraqi dinar before the
1991 Gulf War fetched 3.2 dollars.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan government has allocated 3.5 billion
dirhams (350 million U.S. dollars) to finance an emergency project
to alleviate the serious consequences of a drought that hit
several regions in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural production has declined during the current farming
season by about 40 percent as compared to the previous years due
to the scarcity of rainfall, the rise in temperature and too weak
eastern winds, the Arab daily Al Hayat Monday quoted Agriculture
Minister Abdelaziz Belfkih as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that gross domestic product (GDP) would decline by
less than 0.2 percent by the end of 1999 due to agriculture which
depends on rainfall.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the wheat import bill will rise to about
400 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
