<HEADLINE> Cambodian KR Leaders May Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia may need another two
months to try the detained Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok and jail
executor Duch, the military court's investigating judge said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no sufficient document to try them now, so we need
more time to investigate, maybe at least two months," Ngin Sam Ann
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said, "more witnesses will be questioned to fill up the
investigation," but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Ngin Sam Ann said, so far, ten people have been questioned by
the court as witnesses of Ta Mok's case.
</P>
<P>
Under the Cambodia law, Ta Mok, 72, can only be legally
detained for six months before he faces trial. So far, Ta Mok has
already been detained in Phnom Penh Military Prosecution
Department for nearly four months since he was arrested on March
6.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Kaing Khek Lev, the 56-year-old security
services chief alias "Duch," was brought into protective custody
on May 9 and charged the next day.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen earlier said in a speech to Cambodian
ambassadors that "Ta Mok can be tried in two phases. In the first
phase, he would be tried under a law outlawing the Khmer Rouge so
that his detention can be continued."
</P>
<P>
"In the second phase," said Hun Sen "Ta Mok would face a law on
genocide that meets international standards." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
