<HEADLINE> Vietnam Gets US$885 Million of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has approved 885 million
U.S. dollars in new foreign direct investment (FDI) in the first
half of 1999, a 38-percent drop from the same period of last year,
Vietnam's business newspaper The Saigon Times Daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The investment was for 109 new projects with a total registered
capital of 601 million dollars and for 58 others which are already
under operation and are allowed to increase investment capital,
the daily quoted Vietnam's Ministry of Planning and Investment as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four countries and regions have invested in Vietnam in
the period, with Taiwan, South Korea and Japan topping the list.
</P>
<P>
A total of 24 cities and provinces in the country have absorbed
FDI, but most investment projects have gone to localities with
good infrastructure and large consumer markets. Hanoi has
attracted most FDI in the period with 204.6 million dollars in 11
projects.
</P>
<P>
Currently about 2,200 projects are operational in Vietnam, with
a total registered capital of 36 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
