<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Singapore Sign Document on Industrial Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and Singapore
working teams on Suzhou Industrial Park (SIP) signed here Monday a
memorandum of understanding (MoU) on the further development of
SIP.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Chinese team leader Liang Baohua said
the two sides have resolved all outstanding commercial issues and
reached consensus on major issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Singapore team leader Khaw Boon Wan, permanent secretary of the
Singapore Ministry of Trade and Industry, said the signing of the
MoU marks a new phase in SIP's development and has put the SIP
project on a more successful footing.
</P>
<P>
The MoU emphasized that SIP has made impressive progress in the
last five years and met the targets of the initial phase by
becoming one of China's fastest-growing and most competitive
development zones.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that positive results have also been achieved in
adapting Singapore's economic management and public administration
experience in developing the industrial park.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that these achievements of SIP are the result of
the friendly cooperation and joint efforts between China and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In the MoU, both sides agreed that the current priority of
China-Singapore Suzhou Industrial Park Development Co. Ltd. is to
concentrate on developing the first eight square kilometers and
strive to complete it by January 2001 so that it can serve as a
model for the remainder of the 70 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed that CSSD will adjust the proportions of
shares held by the Chinese and Singapore consortiums respectively
from January 1, 2001, and at the same time the majority
shareholder's responsibility of large tract development will be
handed over to the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
Under the MoU, shareholding of the Chinese side will increase
from 35 percent to 65 percent while the shares held by the
Singapore side will come down from 65 percent to 35 percent after
the scheduled adjustment takes effect.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed that adaptation of Singapore's
experience will be accelerated so as to train and groom a team of
Chinese managers who are able to effectively take over the
management responsibility.
</P>
<P>
They declared that they will continue to take every possible
measure to speed up SIP's development and further strengthen their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Liang reaffirmed that Jiangsu Province and Suzhou Municipality,
where SIP is located, will continue to give priority to and take
every effective measure to speed up SIP development.
</P>
<P>
Khaw Boon Wan also expressed his belief that this transition
will take place smoothly and reaffirmed Singapore's strong desire
to promote economic cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to develop SIP was signed by the Chinese and
Singapore governments in February 1994 and the SIP project is the
largest cooperation project between the two governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City to Host Investment Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital of south China's
Hainan Province, is to host a week-long economic and trade
promotion drive to attract overseas and domestic investment.
</P>
<P>
It will take place from November 9-28 and incorporates two
fairs: the 1999 Haikou Economic and Trade Fair which will focus on
development of the city's foreign trade and economic and
technological cooperation with overseas partners. The fair on
Capital Operation of Chinese Private Enterprises will feature a
display of the development and prospects of private enterprises as
well as providing a chance to speed up exchanges between the firms.
</P>
