<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Fight to Protect 600-Year Old Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,000 residents in this
capital of central China's Hunan Province have joined a volunteer
drive to protect a 600-year old well in the city.
</P>
<P>
A famous city trademark, the well was built in the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644) and has since been used by local people. Every day,
more than 1,000 people still fetch water from the well.
</P>
<P>
But for the past several months, the area around the well has
been occupied by a construction company building a series of
apartment blocks in the area. And about 4.7 hectares of the land
around the well have been leveled and many trees cut down.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the city's 1,000 ancient wells have dried up owing to
the mushrooming of modern construction projects in recent years,"
said a resident, who explained that the well is the only one left
which provides drinkable water. More important, it is a historical
relic, he added.
</P>
<P>
The construction work around the well has stopped following
strong protests by local residents, who are still keeping an eye
on the well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Progress Made upon ARATS' President's Taiwan Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS) and Taiwan's Straits Exchange
Foundation (SEF) made progress here today on the arrangements for
ARATS President Wang Daohan's autumn visit to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Li Yafei, ARATS vice secretary-general, and Jan Jyh-horng, SEF
deputy secretary-general, met in Beijing today and continued to
exchange views upon implementing the four point agreement reached
by ARATS President Wang Daohan and SEF Chairman Koo Chen-fu during
their second meeting in Shanghai last October.
</P>
<P>
According to Li's and Jan's brief after the meeting, SEF
proposed a four point principle in receiving Wang in Taiwan, which
was interpreted as being "safe, comfortable, sincere and
constructive." SEF also named Wang's visit as "a trip to get to
know Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
The ARATS pointed out that Wang's Taiwan visit would be a high
level dialogue between the heads of the two organizations, which
would include continued and deepened dialogue on politics and
economy.
</P>
<P>
"It was inappropriate, therefore, to simply define Wang's visit
as 'a trip to get to know Taiwan'," said Li, noting that
compatriots across the Straits hoped that Wang's Taiwan visit
would push forward dialogue and negotiations across the Straits,
and bring about improvements and developments of across-the-
Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the preparatory work for Wang's Taiwan visit should
focus on furthered dialogue between the heads of the two
organizations, which should consequently include scheduling.
</P>
<P>
SEF offered two choices for the timing of Wang's visit: from
September 12 to 19 or October 12 to 19. The specific date should
be decided after it was reported to ARATS President Wang Daohan.
</P>
<P>
On the duration of Wang's stay in Taiwan, SEF, which has
proposed nine days, agreed to ARATS plan of seven days.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations also agreed that the route of Wang's
visit would be from Taipei to Kaohsiung.
</P>
<P>
On other arrangements for Wang-Koo's meeting in Taiwan, ARATS
suggested two dialogues: one would be formal, the other exchanging
views with limited participation. The two organizations would
maintain communication in various forms so as to make proper
preparations for Wang's future visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
