<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG PM Denies Possibility of Government Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinean (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate Monday refused to concede that he would lose
government after his major coalition partner deserted him and
joined the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press said Skate is facing defeat in
a no-confidence vote on or after July 13 after the largest party
in the ruling coalition withdrew its support for his already
shaky, 23-month-old government.
</P>
<P>
People's Democratic Movement (PDM) leader Mekere Morauta Monday
announced that his party would quit its partnership with Skate's
PNG First party, taking 40 defectors across to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Mekere, opposition leader Bernard Narokobi and the leader of
the Advance PNG party, Speaker John Pundari, said they would form
a new coalition to unseat what they described as Skate's
dictatorial and unpopular government.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders claimed that the opposition now numbered 81
in a parliament of 103 sitting MPs: 40 from the PDM, 25 from the
Advance PNG and 16 from other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders said they would discuss the leadership of an
alternative government over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
However, it was expected that Mekere, as the leader of the
largest party in the new-look opposition, would be offered the
prime ministership, the Australian wire service said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Skate told the wire service that the prime
minister was confident of retaining support and would not bow to
pressure to recall the parliament before July 13.
</P>
<P>
"The pm is continuing to work as normal," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the desertion by the PDM would make Skate
work harder to attract support over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
On the weekend, six of Skate's cabinet ministers announced that
they were quitting PNG First -- five joined Mekere's PDM and the
other Pundari's Advance PNG.
</P>
<P>
Mekere was quoted as telling reporters Monday, "The People's
Democratic Movement can no longer be part of a government that is
dictatorial and generally incompetent."
</P>
<P>
He accused the government of failing to secure adequate
international funding or control the 22-percent inflation rate and
the plunging value of the national currency, the kina.
</P>
<P>
Mekere, who was fisheries minister in the Skate government, was
dismissed from the cabinet with three other PDM ministers earlier
this month but said at the time that the PDM would continue to
stay in the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
