<HEADLINE> China to Re-Train All Judicial Personnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- All staff in China's judicial
administrations are to be sent back to school in three years to
improve the quality of the judiciary's work, according to China's
Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"The program, which will take place over the next three years,
is part of a massive effort to improve the quality of all judicial
workers in the country," said minister of justice Gao Changli at a
meeting held recently in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Gao, various forms of on-the-job training courses
will also be introduced and staff will be re-educated in rotation.
</P>
<P>
Also being introduced is a series of entrance exams for new
recruits.
</P>
<P>
"All would be judicial workers must pass these exams," Gao said.
"And unqualified officials must be dismissed forthwith."
</P>
<P>
China has adopted the policy of governing the country according
to law and therefore the judicial sector has stepped up efforts to
raise its law enforcement levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
