<HEADLINE> 25,000 Tons of Crude Oil Leaked in Australian Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- About 25,000 tons of crude oil
leaked Monday into the sea from the offshore oil refinery at Port
Stanvac, south of the coastal Australian city of Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
In an 11-hour operation, emergency response crews attempted to
recover or disperse the one kilometer-long slick, which is up to
250 meters-wide and only three kilometers offshore, the Australian
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Mobil Oil Australia, which operates the refinery, said it
appeared the leak occurred early Monday morning after crude oil
carrier Chanda had completed its oil discharge through a floating
hose system.
</P>
<P>
"A full investigation into the incident has begun," the company
said.
</P>
<P>
"It appears at this stage that the oil did not leak from the
ship, but from the floating hose system."
</P>
<P>
About 100 people took part in the clean-up operation, with two
helicopters used to assess the extent of the slick.
</P>
<P>
Two aircraft sprayed dispersants on the oil while eight boats
scooped it up or broke it up through a process called mechanical
agitation.
</P>
<P>
At this stage, no oil has been found washed up the beach and no
wildlife is known to have been affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
