<HEADLINE> NPC Approves Laws on Crimes by Minors and Macao Garrison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislative body, the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, approved
three important laws here today at the end of its week long
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Legislation on the prevention of crimes by minors, the garrison
for the Macao Special Administrative Region and donations to
public welfare were passed, along with other decisions.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee who presided
over today's meeting, said that children make up nearly a third of
China's total population and the passing of the law dealing with
preventing crimes by minors is of great significance.
</P>
<P>
The law on the garrison in Macao, which will return to China on
December 20 this year, embodies the basic principle of "one
country, two systems", Li said.
</P>
<P>
"The legislation will play a major role in maintaining the
country's sovereignty, unity, territorial integrity and the
security of the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the donation law, Li expressed the belief that the
legitimate rights and interests of both donors and beneficiaries
will be fully protected.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the NPC Standing Committee also made
interpretations of relevant articles of the Basic Law of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
"It is both necessary and appropriate for the NPC Standing
Committee to make the interpretations," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The move is in the overall interests of Hong Kong and will help
promote and maintain its long term prosperity and stability, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
