<HEADLINE> China Has 5 Percent of World's Ship-building Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China had five percent of world
total orders of 2,635 new ships by the end of 1998, ranking fifth
globally, according to the Shanghai Shipping Exchange Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Bureau also reveals that Greek shipping
companies have decided recently to order a further 24 vessels from
Chinese shipyards in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, companies in the Middle East also intend to
order five 300,000-ton ships valued at a total of 600 million U.S.
dollars from China.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that China's ship-building industry, the
world's third largest following Japan and the Republic of Korea (
ROK), has greatly improved its international competitiveness,
prompting Europeans to pay more attention to its expertise.
</P>
<P>
China's ship-building capacity has rapidly increased to six
million tons since the country initiated its policy of reform and
opening-up in the late 1970s. 
</P>
