<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK External Trade Shows Moderate Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's exports were still
on the decline in May on a year-on-year basis but the rate of
decline moderated significantly from that recorded since the
second part of 1998.
</P>
<P>
These are shown in the external trade figures for May 1999
released Monday by the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The value of total exports (comprising re-exports and domestic
exports) in May 1999 decreased by 4.1 percent from a year earlier
to 108.6 billion HK dollars (13.9 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Within this total, the value of re-exports was down by 2.3
percent to 94.8 billion HK dollars (12.2 billion U.S. dollars),
and that of domestic exports by 15 percent to 13.8 billion HK
dollars (1.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Concurrently, the value of imports in May 1999 fell by 12.5
percent from a year earlier to 108.9 billion HK dollars (14
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A visible trade deficit of 300 million HK dollars (38.5 million
U.S. dollars) was recorded in May 1999, which was significantly
smaller than the deficit of 11.2 billion HK dollars (1.4 billion U.
S. dollars) recorded in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of 1999 as a whole, the value of
total exports was down by 7.8 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman pointed out that export
performance improved further in May 1999. With the continued
downward adjustment in export prices, the decline in the volume of
total exports should have largely bottomed out in May.
</P>
<P>
This was mainly due to a rebound in exports to a number of East
Asian markets as the regional economic situation recovered, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the visible trade deficit continued to
narrow so far this year mainly due to a decline in the intake of
goods for local use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
