<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh's Seafood Sector Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The seafood sector of Bangladesh has
become the third major foreign exchange earner for the country as
it has been developing rapidly since the country won independence
in 1971.
</P>
<P>
The number of fish processing plants has increased from 15 to
128 during the last 25 years and foreign exchange earnings from
the sector have increased from a trickle of 3.17 million U.S.
dollars in the 1972-73 fiscal year to 321 million dollars in the
1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The seafood sector now ranks third among the country's export
items, next to the ready-made garments and knitwear sectors in
terms of foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
As a riverine deltaic country, crisscrossed by several mighty
rivers such as the Ganges, Brahmaputra and Padma and numerous
canals, Bangladesh, with its tropical climate, is ideally-located
and offers a vast reserve of fresh water fish from its inland
water and shrimps and marine products from the Bay of Bengal.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has 330,000 hectares of inland water, which includes
rivers, canals, marshy land, flood plain area and shrimp ponds, in
addition to 480 kilometers of coastline.
</P>
<P>
At present, this South Asian country produces 30,000 tons of
frozen foods annually and around 1.2 million people directly and
10 million people indirectly depend on the sector for their
livelihood. The sector also contributes about 4.7 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Bangladesh held a two-day Dhaka International
Seafood Fair '99, first of its kind in the country, which drew as
many as 35 firms including two from India and one from Britain to
set up stalls at the fair. During the two days, Bangladeshi
seafood exporters received spot orders of about 10.32 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Being convinced of its great potential, the government has
attached due priority to this sector and included it in the
"thrust sectors" during the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
The government has provided certain facilities and incentives
to seafood exporters such as import of duty-free refrigerated vans
and import of duty-free capital machinery by the processing
plants.
</P>
<P>
Under the current export policy (1997-2002), the government has
been taking such measures as scientific cultivation of shrimps,
necessary steps to allocate 40 hectares of land to each of the
owners of fish processing plants with a view to introducing modern
methods of shrimp culture, providing shrimp and fish processing
plants with bank financing in easy terms on a priority basis for
the implementation of the Hazard Analysis and Critical Control and
arranging for duty-free importation of indispensable
quality-control equipment for strengthening quality-control
measures for frozen food.
</P>
<P>
However, the seafood sector in the country is now facing some
problems in its effort for further development.
</P>
<P>
The existing processing plants in the country have a total
capacity of about 250,000 tons of fisheries products, but actually
about 40,000 tons are being processed by about 58 plants because
of the shortage of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the price fall in the international market has already
forced the sector to have a stockpile of shrimps worth about 82.5
million dollars and the sector has incurred huge losses due to the
declining prices, last year's severe flood and the European
Union's restrictions on import.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the price fall, the Bangladesh Frozen Food
Exporters' Association early this month demanded that the
government give a 15-percent cash subsidy on export earnings, but
till now, the government has not agreed to this. The association
has also urged the government to take steps so that the sector
could compete in the international market and called for the
implementation of a report of the Commerce Ministry's task force
to waive about 61.9 million dollars in penal interest on loans
obtained by producers and exporters in the sector.
</P>
<P>
With the concerted efforts of the sector as regard product
diversification and upgrading along with market expansion and
timely intervention of the government, the seafood sector is now
poised to increase its export to 1 billion dollars in the next
five years, the association said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
