<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Be Tougher on Car Hijackers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The South African Justice
Department has announced a new initiative aimed at more rapid and
efficient prosecution of car hijackers in Gauteng Province.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, led by Bulelani Ngcuka, national director of
Public Prosecution, has united existing police anti-hijacking
efforts with a team of prosecutors and detectives based in the
courts and offices around Johannesburg, the department said in a
statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Car hijacking has become the most feared crime for South
African motorists, particularly those staying or frequenting
Gauteng province, to such an extent that, most night drivers
religiously choose to risk getting hefty traffic fines by ignoring
yield and stop signs for fear of becoming victims of this violent
crime," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Since March 1, all serious car related crimes from all
Johannesburg Police Stations and the police anti-hijacking unit,
previously split between multiple courts with little coordination,
are now directed to the Task Force for early case assessment, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Following assessment, the Task Force then directs further
investigation and prosecutes cases aggressively in regional
courts.
</P>
<P>
Finally, together with the police, the Investigating
Directorate on Organized Crime , and the community, the Task Force
analyses patterns of cases and engages in problem-solving efforts
with local communities, police, and other stake holders to develop
further strategies to prevent car hijacking.
</P>
<P>
The anti-car hijacking initiative brings in two new resources
to the prosecution of car hijacking cases in Johannesburg: the
Investigating Directorate on Organized Crime, which uses the new
powers of the National Prosecuting Authority to investigate and
bring the most serious car hijacking cases to trial; and the
Prosecution Task force on Hijacking, based at the Johannesburg
Magistrates Court which analyzes all new car hijacking and
car-related cases, and also investigate and work with prosecutors
on all cases that the IDOC does not handle.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department of Justice, the anti-hijacking
initiative was designed to develop the following:
</P>
<P>
-- communication systems between local prosecutors and their
supervisors;
</P>
<P>
-- case screening systems and information technology;
</P>
<P>
-- practical means for prosecutors to guide local police
investigators;
</P>
<P>
-- an automated system to collect statistics about conviction
rates, priority crimes, withdrawals, etc. as well as reduce fraud
and corruption;
</P>
<P>
-- a code of conduct for prosecutors; and,
</P>
<P>
-- practical methods to communicate more regularly with
witnesses, victims, and community structures.
</P>
<P>
"The initiative has been designed to demonstrate that a
replicable strategic enforcement effort, uniting prosecution,
police, and community, can achieve real reductions in crime," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The goal is not just to reduce hijacking, but to inspire and
instruct similar strategic efforts against other crime problems,"
it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
