<HEADLINE> Renovation of Tian'anmen Rostrum Nearing End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The renovation of the Tian'anmen
Rostrum, the most renowned ancient building in China, is nearing
its end with the approach of the 50th anniversary of the founding
of New China.
</P>
<P>
Located at the main gate of the Imperial Forbidden City, the
582-year-old rostrum was where the old emperors would make public
decrees. And it was there on October 1, 1949, that Chairman Mao
Zedong announced to the Chinese people the founding of the People'
s Republic of China. It has remained a place for important
ceremonies ever since.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project has involved many activities, including
painting the walls, renewing the lightning-prevention devices,
improving the electrical circuits and fire fighting equipment,
refurbishing wooden structures, replacing banisters on stairways
and cleaning tiles.
</P>
<P>
The reviewing stand of the rostrum has also been refurbished
along with a repaving of the street level. Even the red lanterns
hanging from the rostrum have been replaced by new ones, with the
lighting also improved to enhance the outlook of the building at
night.
</P>
<P>
The rostrum was first opened to visitors in 1988, and has
received more than 18 million domestic and overseas tourists since
then.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
