<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province to Build More Youth Hostels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
plans to build 20 more youth hostels in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu Weixiong, head of Guangdong Provincial Tourism
Administration, the province has led the nation by opening three
international hostels for students in Guangzhou, the provincial
capital, Zhuhai and Zhaoqing cities in the same province, in late
1998.
</P>
<P>
Administrators of the three hostels recently received a dozen
reservation letters from abroad via a room booking network through
the International Youth Hostel Federation.
</P>
<P>
Youth hostel administrative officials from 80 countries will
make an inspection tour to this south Chinese province in August.
In turn, Guangdong Province will send 80 Chinese students to
inspect youth hostels in Europe in a bid to improve youth hostels
in China.
</P>
<P>
Youth hostels are safe with proper sanitation facilities but
cost less than hotels. They first appeared in Germany in 1912.
The International Youth Hostel Federation now has 4,500 youth
hostels listed and has grown into the world's biggest
accommodation organization.
</P>
<P>
The federation now has 60 member countries and 40 non-member
countries also using the facilities, with the individual
memberships totaling 3.5 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
