<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor Factions Agree to Accept Vote Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- East Timor's pro-integration and
pro-independence groups attending a reconciliation conference here
have expressed support for a peaceful reconciliation process and
acceptance of the vote results on self determination.
</P>
<P>
Opening the second session of the second round of the Dare
dialogue and reconciliation conference here Monday, Dili Bishop
Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo said the meeting is aimed at bringing
the East Timorese to an attitude of listening to each other and
respecting the result of direct balloting.
</P>
<P>
"Please avoid personal or group problems which could lead to a
conflict of interest in each party," Belo said.
</P>
<P>
Tamrat Samuel, assistant of Jamsheed Marker, the U.N. Special
envoy for East Timor, said the authorities should also take note
of human factors involved in the popular consultation, so both
pro- and anti-integration groups can accept the result of the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
Anna Gomes, head of the Portuguese Interest Section here, who
represents the Portugal government, said the country has a
commitment to accept whatever the result is of the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Ambassador At Large FX Lopes da Cruz, representing
the pro-integration group, said if both parties could not find a
real solution for the territory, it will harm the East Timorese in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Jailed rebel leader Jose Alexandre "Xanana" Gusmao, who
represents the anti-integration group, has asked all East Timorese
to change the conflict into a new and better situation for peace
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The second-round meeting was a continuation of a successful
church-sponsored conference held in Dare village, west of Dili,
capital of East Timor, in September last year. Like the first Dare
talks, the second-round conference is jointly sponsored by Carlos
Filipe Ximenes Belo and Baucau Bishop Basilio do Nascimento.
</P>
<P>
The second-round conference is divided into two session. The
first session, held in the same hotel on Friday and Saturday,
involved only representatives from East Timor, without East
Timorese living in exile.
</P>
<P>
The second session is attended by 60 participants from both
groups, U.S. Ambassador J. Stapleton Roy, Australian Ambassador
John McCharty, some representatives from the European Union,
Japan, Italy, France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the talks will issue a joint communique on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold the direct ballot in August this year.
</P>
<P>
The ballot will allow the territory's people to choose whether
their homeland should become an autonomous region within Indonesia
or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
