<HEADLINE> Tian'anmen Square Re-opens to Public (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The world's biggest square today
re-opened to the public after an eight-month renovation during
which time the work was carried out behind a high, metal barrier.
</P>
<P>
The massive face-lift of Tian'anmen Square began in October
last year but the fencing finally came down last night as more
than 5,000 people rushed to watch the traditional flag raising
ceremony at 4.00 am
</P>
<P>
Entering the new square, which is as big as nine football
pitches, the most eye-catching sight is the neat, pink granite
paving flags. And in today's early dawn dragonflies and swallows
hovered over the sweeping new lawns which are a feature of the
east and west sides of the square.
</P>
<P>
The crowd enthusiastically sang the Chinese national anthem and
the "East Is Red", a traditional song lauding late Chairman Mao
Zedong, who announced the founding of the People's Republic on the
Tian'anmen Rostrum on October 1, 1949.
</P>
<P>
Just before 8:00 am, thousands of tourists, in groups or
individually, arrived in the square which was soon buzzing with
different dialects and foreign languages; a once familiar babble
before it closed.
</P>
<P>
Among the crowds, there were urban youngsters in fashionable
clothes and farmers wearing traditional Chinese shoes made of
cloth. And then came the disabled in armchairs and babies in
handcarts pushed by their parents.
</P>
<P>
An 80-year old woman, who said her surname was Feng, had come
from remote Jiangxi province by airplane. "I have never visited
our capital before and I want to visit Chairman Mao's Mausoleum,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
There was an endless queue in front of the mausoleum and many
people explained that they knew the opening times from TV and
newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Beirut's Power Generators Roar Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Like most of the residents in
Beirut and its suburbs, Ali Mohammed dusted off his old generator
and made it in order again to supply electricity for his cloth
shop.
</P>
<P>
"My business is already bad and I can't afford additional
expenses. The current two-hour electricity is not far enough for
me," Mohammed told Xinhua Sunday in his shop in the capital's
commercial street of Hamra.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't used generators for three years and the Israeli
attack brought us to the painful past overnight," the 50-year-old
businessman said with tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
He thought of his eight-year-old daughter which was killed in
the 1996 Israeli "Grapes of Wrath" operations, which claimed at
least 200 people's lives, most of them civilians.
</P>
<P>
Thursday night, Israel launched the biggest air strike on
Lebanon since the 1996 onslaught, killing eight Lebanese and
wounding over 60 others.
</P>
<P>
Apart from three bridges linking the capital and its south and
a telephone relay station, the country's two power stations which
feed electricity to Beirut and its surrounding areas, were also
destroyed by the 10-hour blitz.
</P>
<P>
The strike plunged much of the capital into darkness and
electricity supply has to be limited to two or three hours a day.
</P>
<P>
As the temperature and humidity continue to climb, the city
will swelter because there is no refrigeration nor air
conditioning. Beirut citizens won't even be able to use electric
fans.
</P>
<P>
"We'll connect electricity lines from different areas to
supply Beirut with power before we can begin repairing the
plants," said George Mouawad, Director General of Electricite du
Liban (EDL).
</P>
<P>
"Our priority is to supply water pumping stations, telephone
exchanges, and the grain silos at the port," he added.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Salim Hoss said the latest damage is practically
immeasurable since it coincides with the start of a promising
tourist season.
</P>
<P>
Billionaire Saudi Prince Alwaleed bin Talal has promised to
cover the total cost of repairing the Jamhour and Bsalim power
plants, estimated at around 30 million U.S. dollars while Syria
offered electricity emergency supply.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis don't want to see Lebanese reconstruction go
forward. They want to see us pay billions of dollars to rebuild
our bridges and restore our electricity and never have the chance
to move forward," said the irate Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has spent hundreds of millions of dollars during the
1990s on restoring its electrical power supplies and grid from the
damages of the 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
"They're paralyzing the country when our economy is already
languishing," said Hussein Sami, 47, who runs a restaurant in
Arshrafieh, Beirut's another famous commercial area.
</P>
<P>
With the announcement by EDL that power supply will be
increased to 12 hours a day in Beirut from Monday, the clatter of
private generators will drop, but the effect of Israel's strike on
the country's economy is turning clearer.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed is sitting alone in his once crowded shop to wait for
the frightened customers, most of whom are staying at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tian'anmen Square Re-opens to Public (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There are no stunning changes in the square," commented Yang
Shukun, who lives just behind the Great Hall of the People. "It is
still the familiar and amiable square. However, it looks wider and
more splendid."
</P>
<P>
"It is very beautiful, and it is the world's largest after all,
" said Michael Wechsler, from New York's Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of new lamp standards have been installed to
illuminate the square at night, the Monument to the People's
Heroes and other landmarks, which had become weather-beaten and
affected by pollution, have been cleaned up while powerful
loudspeakers have replaced the older tinny sounding ones.
</P>
<P>
Meng Wenqing, an architect from south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, said that after examining the joints of the
stones and the drainage systems, he found that state of the art
techniques had been used in the restoration work.
</P>
<P>
The original site of Tian'anmen Square was a courtyard of the
Imperial Palace where the ordinary people were not allowed to
enter. It was expanded into the existing vast area in 1959 and the
latest face-lift will enable it to proudly stage the grand Gala of
the 50th founding anniversary of New China on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Wei Zhihe, a worker who was involved in the first renovation 40
years ago, said that it was right that the square should have been
renovated again so as to receive more tourists, hold bigger mass
activities and to demonstrate the pride of a rising China in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
For many years, Chinese people have regarded visiting Beijing
as one of the biggest pleasures in their lives. When they arrive
they almost invariably head for Tian'anmen Square which is known
as "The Heart of China".  
</P>
</TEXT>
