<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Chinese Trades Fading Away (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Although business had been slack
for years, Zhang Fugen, a Chinese who had been making a living by
writing letters for the illiterate, felt it hard to face when it
really came to the time that he had to give up the job.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a resident in the city of Lianyungang, east China's
Jiangsu Province, closed his letter-writing business in 1994,
since few customers came to him for help.
</P>
<P>
"Who would have come to me?" said the man, 65, now owner of a
VCD shop. "Young people can all write, and there are telephones
and even computers everywhere."
</P>
<P>
Zhang now earns much more than he did before. "And I'm proud I'
ve been engaged in one of the newest industries," he said, while
presenting some newly released VCDs to customers.
</P>
<P>
Zhang is only one of an increasing number of Chinese who have
lost their original jobs in some traditional trades that have been
fading away over the past few decades.
</P>
<P>
There are no official figures as to exactly how many trades
have disappeared or are withering away across the country, but Tao
Siyan, China's first doctor of folklore and professor with the
Dongnan University in Jiangsu Province, lists about a dozen, such
as writing letters for illiterate people, supplying boiled water,
selling coffins, and repairing pans and bowls.
</P>
<P>
"These trades had played a big role in China for generations,"
Tao said. "But their functions have become less and less useful
due to China's rapid economic and social development."
</P>
<P>
"A trade disappears naturally if it is no longer needed by
society," Tao added. "And the faster the society progresses, the
faster new trades replace old ones."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
