<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Chinese Trades Fading Away (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Tao, the past two decades have seen the most
dramatic restructuring in China's lines of business as new ideas,
advanced technologies, as well as various new products were
introduced and developed during the country's reform, opening up
and the modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of China's telephone users has
topped 110 million, the second largest in the world, and that of
Internet users in the country has reached 2.5 million,
representing a great change in methods of communication.
</P>
<P>
The "tiger stove", which got its name because of its bulky
shape and a chimney like a tiger's tail, was a popular boiled
water supplier for some 200 years in many parts of east China,
when there was no convenient fuel available but wood and coal. In
Shanghai alone, there were 900 such stoves.
</P>
<P>
Yet they are rarely seen now because local residents use gas
and electrical stoves and no longer go to "tiger stove" shops for
boiled water.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have accelerated the elimination of "tiger
stoves", for the coal and wood that fueled them produced an
enormous amount of dust and sulfur dioxide, causing serious
pollution.
</P>
<P>
"What the nation has been encouraging is the development of new
and high-tech industries, and trades that are environment-friendly
or bring about marketable products," explained Shanghai Mayor Xu
Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
The tools of outdated trades are not all eliminated, however,
as museums are more than ready to accommodate them. The Nanjing
Folklore Museum, set up ten years ago in Nanjing, the provincial
capital of Jiangsu, has collected hundreds of such tools,
including those used for repairing "tiger stoves", cane chairs,
and wooden water buckets.
</P>
<P>
"These trades constitute a major part of Chinese history and
culture," said Yang Tianqi, deputy curator of the museum. "People
may learn something by looking at them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Volunteers Arrive in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-four international
volunteers arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, via special
flights from Darwin, Australia, on Monday to help conduct the
territory's August direct ballot, the Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The volunteers will be immediately posted in all districts of
East Timor to carry out their jobs, such as conducting the
registration of voters and making preparations for polling
stations," said David Wimhurst, spokesman of the United Nations
Assistance Mission in East Timor (UNAMET).
</P>
<P>
He said the volunteers are experienced in carrying out
elections or plebiscites in many countries and they also attended
an intensive training course in Darwin for such purposes.
</P>
<P>
Wimhurst also said some 100 cars were unloaded in the Baucau
air base, East Timor, from a transport plane which brought them
from Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Another delivery of 100 cars is also expected in East Timor
next week to help facilitate the work of UNAMET in the territory,
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Wimhurst, some 70 U.N. civilian policemen who
arrived in Dili last week have now been assigned to several
district capitals, like Dili, Aileu, Liquica, Baucau, Maliana,
Ermera, Suai and Same.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5,
the United Nations will send civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police maintain law and order. A
key function will be to disarm rival factions that are either for
or against the territory's independence.
</P>
<P>
Last week, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan ordered a two-week
delay of the ballot which was originally scheduled for August 8,
citing security and logistics concerns.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
