<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Export 160,000 Tons of Maize in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique will have 160,000 tons
of maize and 27,000 tons of millet for export in 1998/1999
agricultural year ending June 30, 1999, Mozambican Minister of
Agriculture and Fisheries Carlos do Rosario has said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that Mozambique has so much surplus of
these two kinds of crops in two decades," do Rosario said
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Noticias newspaper Monday quoted the minister as saying
that Mozambique is expected to harvest 1.8 million tons of grain
this year, a 10 percent increase over last year, although 63,000
hectares of farm land have been flooded this agricultural year.
</P>
<P>
However, do Rosario admitted that this year Mozambique needs to
import 64,000 tons of rice and 190,000 tons of wheat to cover the
shortage.
</P>
<P>
Yet the minister noted that the food shortage in Mozambique had
 gradually dropped to 201,000 tons from 490,000 tons in 1996,
680,000 tons in 1994 and 1.2 million tons in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increased grain production to a 300 million
U.S. dollars investment in agriculture under the National
Agricultural Development Program, good seeds offered to farmers by
his government and the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization, an
increased planting area of 3.5 million hectares and a favorable
climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
