<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most of Zambian Children Out of School: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- About 85 percent of Zambian
children of school going age are out of school, Zambian Education
Minister Godfrey Miyanda has said in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"About 85 percent of children of schools going age are unable
to enter into school or attend any type of formal education," the
Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted Miyanda as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister noted that in 1996, the government
approved a new education policy titled "Educating our Future"
which provided a policy framework and strategies to guide the
provision and delivery of education in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 United Nations Children's Fund's (UNICEF)
report, Zambia and other developing countries spend 70 billion
U.S. dollars on education every year.
</P>
<P>
Over 8.2 million children aged 14 or younger have lost their
parents through AIDS and 7.8 million of these children are in
sub-Saharan Africa, said the UNICEF report.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan Africa has an average gross national product (GNP)
per capita income of 528 dollars as compared to industrialized
countries's GNP per capita of 27,086 dollars, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
