<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Speaker Not to Participate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iranian sitting conservative Majlis
(parliament) Speaker Nateq Nouri will not take part in the next
Majlis elections slated for February 2000.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the right-wing (conservative) factions have
confirmed Nouri's decision, citing tiredness and consolidating the
conservative political group, the Association of Militant Mullahs
in Tehran (AMM), as the main reasons behind his decision.
</P>
<P>
The unsuitable political situation for the conservatives and
Nouri's failure in 1997 presidential elections forced him to
change his mind, the pro-moderate daily Salam said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nouri, born in 1943, served as Interior Minister in 1981-1985
and was elected Majlis Speaker for eight terms since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Following their failure in the February elections for local
city and village councils this year, the conservatives started
reorganization of their groups and parties, particularly the
prominent AMM, in which top Iranian conservative leaders have
memberships.
</P>
<P>
Both the moderates and conservatives have started their
campaigns for the sixth Majlis elections and pinned their hope on
the elections for a change in the country's power balance.
</P>
<P>
Some rumors said that the moderate factions have urged former
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani to run for the Majlis speaker
in order to defeat the conservatives, who are dominating the
Majlis, and to ensure the majority for the moderates, the main
supporters of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani served as Majlis speaker for 9 years until he
was elected president for two four-year terms in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
