<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas: Coalition Talks Make Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The coalition talks between One
Israel headed by Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak and the
Shas party have made progress and the two sides are expected to
reach an agreement soon, local media reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shas's delegation met with One Israel's negotiating team again
Sunday night and the talks centered more on finalizing the
coalition policy guidelines than on the distribution of cabinet
portfolios, Shas's delegation head, Labor and Social Affairs
Minister Eli Ishai was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Shas negotiators are expected to report to party spiritual
leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef and the Council of Torah Sages later
Monday and the council is expected to make its final decision on
whether to join the coalition soon.
</P>
<P>
Shas is angry with Barak's earlier decision to let Yisrael
Ba'aliya's leader Natan Sharansky take the finance portfolio which
Shas has held for 15 years, threatening not to join Barak's
coalition.
</P>
<P>
But during Sunday night's meeting, Ishai told One Israel that
Shas wants to hold the National Infrastructure Ministry, including
authorities over the Public Works Department and the Israel Lands
Administration, both of which Barak have already removed from the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Shas also wants to hold the Labor and Social
Affairs Ministry, the Health Ministry and a deputy prime minister
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Religious Affairs Ministry has not been settled so
far, with Shas refusing to accept it with a rotation with the
National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
One Israel's talks with the United Torah Judaism also ran into
Monday morning and the two sides are said to be very close to
signing a coalition agreement, having almost reached a compromise
on drafting religious students into the army.
</P>
<P>
Barak is also scheduled to hold talks with interim Likud
leader Ariel Sharon Monday afternoon to ask Sharon to give a
final say whether the Likud is to join the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Barak only has until this Friday to present his coalition list
to the Knesset (parliament), under law that a prime minister has
45 days to form a government after elections.
</P>
<P>
Till now, Yitzhak Mordechai also has some problems within his
Center party over signing coalition agreement with One Israel.
</P>
<P>
Some key party members are said to be very angry that
Mordechai has already guaranteed himself the Transport Ministry
and deputy prime minister posts alongside a seat in the security
cabinet, but failed to win anything for his colleagues such as
the party's No. 2 figure Amnon Lipkin-Shahak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
