<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Starts Quality Inspection of All Imported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Bureau of
Standards Monday started compulsory quality inspection of all
imported products in a bid to protect the health and safety of the
public.
</P>
<P>
Local media Monday reported that the bureau has decided to
enforce the import inspection regulations stipulated in Government
Notice No. 672 of December 25, 1998 so as to reverse the trend of
importing poor quality goods.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has been nicknamed by the media as a dumping ground
for imported sub-standard and shoddy products for years.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that Tanzania is flooded with sub-standard imported
goods and the public outcry on low quality imported products is
now more evident than ever," said the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory quality inspection is also expected to rescue
local industries which are subjected to unfair competition from
some imported products of poor quality.
</P>
<P>
"As an example, the government published a few months ago
several types of imported dry batteries because they did not meet
national standards and were selling at give-away prices which were
detrimental to locally made products," the statement noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Endangered Tree Discovered in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Forest workers in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region recently discovered nearly 3,000
Normal Dendroglossa trees which are believed to be close the
extinction.
</P>
<P>
The trees which belong to the tree-fern family are located in a
forest farm in Tian'e County in northwestern Guangxi. This kind of
tree is believed one of the oldest species in the world. It is
under state-level protection in China and known as a "living
fossil" similar to the ginkgo.
</P>
<P>
Some of the trees have a diameter of 30 cm and stand dozens of
meters high.
</P>
<P>
The county's subtropical climate provides favorable conditions
for the growth of the trees, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Now relevant departments in the autonomous region have taken
measures to protect the trees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
