<HEADLINE> UAE Firm to Bid for Beirut Rebuilding Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A leading construction company
in Dubai of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will bid for the
rebuilding of two power stations and three bridges in Beirut
damaged by Israeli air strikes last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The company did not want to be identified until the contract
was actually signed, said the Dubai-based Khaleej Times daily
Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Abu Ali, manager of the company's technical
section, a team of engineers from the company is already in
Lebanon carrying out some infrastructure projects there.
</P>
<P>
"We are highly optimistic that we would bag the rebuilding
work, which is estimated to cost around 164 million U.S.
dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have already submitted the proposals with all the required
financial and other details to the authorities," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the usual lengthy process for signing
contracts cannot be applied in a situation like this when bridges
have been completely wrecked and the country is in the dark due to
disruption of power supply.
</P>
<P>
He said the company was ready to start rebuilding one of the
bridges immediately so as to restore access to all parts of
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The potential rival bidders might include a French power
construction firm, Belgium International Co. and a Saudi-French
construction company, he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Lebanon Construction and Development
Authority is expected to take an emergency decision on Monday
morning. The whole matter will be finalized before the end of the
week, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
