<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Develop Capital Market: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China should accelerate the
development of its capital market and industrial restructuring in
order to maintain sustainable growth in the 21st century,
according to a mainstream research institute.
</P>
<P>
A report just completed by the Macroeconomic Research Institute
under the State Development Planning Commission suggests the need
for the securities market to provide a larger share of financing
sources, according to today's China Securities.
</P>
<P>
The report focuses on studies of economic policies needed for
the beginning of the next century and notes that direct financing
should account for a quarter of total fixed-asset investments. It
also points out the need for an expanded market for stocks and
bonds.
</P>
<P>
The report outlines a number of detailed measures which include
encouraging public offerings for profitable state-owned
enterprises, providing companies with different forms of ownership
equal opportunities for listings and placing priority to initial
public offerings (IPOs) offered by high-tech firms in order to
promote technical innovations.
</P>
<P>
It also recommends that the government introduce pension,
insurance, trust and investment funds into the capital market in
conjunction with continued efforts to foster securities investment
funds and ensure more institutional investors enter the market.
</P>
<P>
Economists from the institute urged the government to exert
greater efforts to develop the money market in order to improve
implementation of the country's monetary policies and expand the
insurance and property rights trading markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
