<HEADLINE> Asian Mayors' Forum Starts in Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The second Asian Mayors' Forum was
inaugurated Monday here by Sri Lankan Minister of Provincial
Councils and Local Government Alavi Moulana.
</P>
<P>
"With the increasing trend of urbanization, Asian countries are
going to face many challenges relating to the adequate and
effective delivery of municipal services," Minister Moulana told
the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 25 mayors and city leaders from 12 countries
are attending the three-day forum which "will provide an
opportunity for the exchange of information and experience on
urban governance and serve as a major mechanism for fostering
networking between mayors and cities."
</P>
<P>
Former Mayor of Colombo Karu Jayasuriya made a keynote address
entitled Changing an Organization's Culture.
</P>
<P>
The forum is sponsored by the Asian Development Bank Institute
(ADBI), the U.N. Development Program, the Colombo Plan
Secretariat, the Colombo Municipal Council and a number of
international agencies.
</P>
<P>
The first Asian Mayors' Forum was held in Cebu, the
Philippines, in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony was also addressed by Colombo Mayor Omar
Kamil, ADBI Dean Masaru Yoshitomi and Secretary-General of the
Colombo Plan Secretariat Sarat Chandran.
</P>
<P>
Cities represented at the forum are those in Bangladesh, China,
India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, Laos, the
Philippines, Thailand, Sri Lanka and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
