<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Pumps in 5 BLN Yuan To Boost Scientific Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to boost China's
scientific development the Chinese government is to provide 5
billion yuan (about 603 million U.S. dollars) by the end of 2000
to expand the country's innovation programs.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the Ministry of Science and Technology
told Xinhua today that China expects to be amongst the world's top
10 countries in terms of scientific development by the year 2010
as a result of this initiative.
</P>
<P>
And an official with the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) said
that being at the core of the national technical innovation system,
it has organized all major research programs to be focused on the
needs of China's social development at the beginning of the next
century while also taking into account world tendencies in
scientific development.
</P>
<P>
He said the CAS will focus on agricultural high-technology,
population and health, information science and technology, new
materials, advanced manufacturing techniques, resources and
environment, space science and basic research programs.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the country's highest research organization is
striving to build 100 national research institutions at an
advanced international level and 20 national research centers
focused on integrated sciences.
</P>
<P>
The CAS also listed a number of frontier scientific research
programs as part of its new strategy. They include agro-genom
studies, anti-pest research of major crops, nanometer, new high-
molecular materials, information agro-technology and super
conductive materials and their application.
</P>
<P>
The CAS also emphasized the strategic importance of major
research programs. They include wide-band IP Internet technology,
industrial robots, special robots, Internet security, and the
prospecting of important oil and gold resources.
</P>
<P>
The CAS official believes that their newly launched research
strategy will achieve preliminary results in the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
