<HEADLINE> Philippines Urges WTO to Phase Out Textiles Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will press the
World Trade Organization (WTO) to implement an agreement that
would phase out export quotas on textiles and clothing products,
Manila Bulletin reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This concern will form part of the government's "policy
statement" in relation to the 1999 trade policy review of the
Philippines in the WTO, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum, the nation's chief trade negotiator Edsel
Custodio said that developed countries have mainly chosen to delay
the removal of quotas from the coverage of textiles and clothing
products from the multilateral trading system (MTS) of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO agreements, the Multi Fiber Agreement (MFA) which
imposes export quotas on textiles and clothing products has to be
removed and this sector will be governed under the rules and
disciplines of the MTS.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines had anticipated favorable trading conditions
for its major garments and textiles exports," Custodio said.
</P>
<P>
However, he complained, halfway through the implementation, the
Philippines together with other developing countries is
"experiencing frustration over the slow phase of the integration
into the MTS."
</P>
<P>
The MFA imposes export quotas or the volume of textile and
clothing products that developing countries can ship to developed
economies.
</P>
<P>
The United States accounts for 70 percent of the total quota
market and 60 percent of the Philippines' exports of textile and
clothing products go to this market. Other quota markets include
the European Union and Canada.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines exports of garments continue to falter midway
in the implementation of the Agreement on textiles and clothing,"
Custodio added.
</P>
<P>
Last year the Garments and Textile Exports Board (GTEB)
reported having reached an exports target of 2.9 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Undersecretary Nelly Villafuerte said the
country's export revenues from garments and textile this year may
shrink from 2.9 billion dollars to 2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
