<HEADLINE> Thailand Tightens Security to Prevent Fishing Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Security has been beefed up in the
southern Thai province of Phuket to prevent possible clash between
rival fishing groups over nocturnal anchovy fishing, the Bangkok
Post said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
All marine police patrol boats in the province have been put on
alert to prevent protesting fishermen from blocking the Phuket
bays.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives Ministry has
imposed a ban on anchovy fishing at night using luring lights
following protests by inshore fishermen who blocked the Songkhla
deep-sea port for nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen argued that the practice is wiping out fish
stocks and threatening their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
However, rival fishermen, angered by the ban, are threatening
to launch their protest and block the Phuket port.
</P>
<P>
Provincial authorities are said to be optimistic that the rival
fishermen would be reasonable and resolve the fishing problem
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The two-week blockade of Songkhla port has caused millions of
baht in lost business. Exporters have had to pay higher shipping
costs to get freight trucked to Klong Toey port in Bangkok, for
onward shipping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
