<HEADLINE> Roundup: Three Express Trains Bringing Closer Mainland-HK Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- After Hong Kong's return to the
motherland, the three express cargo trains shuttle back and forth
between China's inland areas and Hong Kong as usual, helping bring
ever closer links between them.
</P>
<P>
The three express trains bound for Hong Kong from Changsha,
Shanghai and Zhengzhou have been operating for 37 years. Over the
past two years since Hong Kong's return to China, the trains have
carried to Hong Kong more than 2.35 million pigs, 65,000 head of
cattle and 90,000 tons of meat, 5,800 tons of eggs as well as a
large quantity of aquatic products, fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
This has helped ensure an ample supply of goods in Hong Kong
and satisfied the daily needs of the local people.
</P>
<P>
With an area of 1,097 square km, Hong Kong's population now
exceeds 6.8 million. Due to Hong Kong's high population density
and limited cultivated land, it has long imported most of its
needs for farm produce.
</P>
<P>
In 1962, thanks to the late Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai's
concern, the three express trains were launched to transport fresh
and frozen foodstuffs to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Now, over 95 percent of pigs and cattle that Hong Kong imports
come from the mainland and over half of frozen meat and aquatic
products are transported here by the trains.
</P>
<P>
The smooth operation of the three express trains across nine
provinces on the mainland all the year round is partly attributed
to the close cooperation between the railway and foreign trade
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The railway departments have formulated rules and regulations
to ensure the trains run smoothly all the time while the foreign
trade departments have set up bases for raising pigs and cattle
and built a dozen stations for services along the railway routes.
</P>
<P>
Since Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, 1997, the three
express trains have been running as smoothly as before. The
operation remained uninterrupted even during the worst floods to
hit some mainland areas.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997 when an avian flu broke out in Hong Kong,
the local government adopted immediate measures to kill chickens
in Hong Kong. To compensate for the shortage, a batch of 38,000
live chickens were transported from the mainland to Hong Kong
during the 1998 Spring Festival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fund Raising Grows in Singapore Venture Capital Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 28 (Xinhua)-- A 1999 survey shows that
Singapore raised 1.1 billion Singapore dollars (647 million U.S.
dollars) of venture capital in 1998, an increase of 15 percent
over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The survey published by the Economic Development Board (EDB) of
Singapore Monday also indicates that Singapore currently houses 82
active fund management groups, both international and home-grown,
which employ around 360 investment professionals and manage a
cumulative total of 8.8 billion Singapore dollars (5.18 billion
U.S. dollars) as of January 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the findings of the EDB venture capital survey,
Singapore-based capital investors committed around 921 million
Singapore dollars (541.8 million U.S. dollars) in 341 investments
worldwide in 1998 while venture capital investments in Singapore
reached 160 million Singapore dollars (94 million U.S. dollars) in
40 companies, accounting for 17 percent of the total and doubling
the amount in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of these 40 Singapore-based companies that received venture
capital funding in 1998, 16 companies, or 40 percent, are in the
seed and early stages which absorbed 33.2 million Singapore
dollars (19.5 million U.S. dollars), or 21 percent of the total
venture capital investment in Singapore in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates that 35 out of the 40 funded
Singapore-based companies were technology-related with over one
thirds being information technology companies.
</P>
<P>
Singapore first created its venture capital group in 1985
within the EDB in a bid to develop a vibrant venture capital
industry in the city state and it targets by 2005 to increase
venture capital professional number by at least 50 percent, and
expand the number of venture capital-backed seed stage companies
by at least 300 and double the fund managed out of Singapore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
