<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Major Trade News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade news in
China between June 21 and 27:
</P>
<P>
-- China is launching its first wholesales commodity center in
New Siberia. The center under construction in the city of
Novosibirsk will be the largest wholesales network exclusively for
Chinese goods in Siberia. Work on the 2,200-sq.m. center is
expected to be completed by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
-- The 10th China Harbin Economic and Trade Talks came to an
end Monday last week in Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang Province,
in northeast China. Contracts worth 3.57 billion U.S. dollars were
signed at the week-long fair, which attracted more than 50,000
participants from over 50 countries and regions, including over 6,
000 overseas businessmen.
</P>
<P>
-- Exports by overseas-funded businesses in China grew for the
first five months of this year, despite a fall in the nation's
overall export volume during the same period. Those ventures
exported 31.9 billion U.S. dollars worth of products in the five
months, an increase of 5.77 percent over the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- A China-Japan joint company to produce steel frames was set
up Tuesday in Baoshan District in China's largest industrial city
of Shanghai. The project, with its first phase of the operation
expected to cost 29.8 million U.S. dollars, is a joint effort
between the China Ocean Shipping Co. and two Japanese companies,
Kawasaki Heavy Industries Ltd. and Itochu Corp.
</P>
<P>
-- China is expected to open one of its leading military ports,
Huludao, in northeastern China's Liaoning Province, to
international commercial shipping later this year, government
sources announced in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province, last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- China will become one of the world's largest jewelry
production centers by early next century, with projections calling
for annual sales to hit 150 billion yuan (19 billion US dollars),
experts with the China Gem Association predict.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (
MOFTEC), Shi Guangsheng, urged enterprises to expand exports by
all means on Wednesday. Shi said he believed China could realize
growth in exports this year if enterprises use their advantages as
much as possible.
</P>
<P>
-- China is endeavoring to create a more stable and favorable
policy environment, and a more fair and open competition
environment for overseas investors, MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng
told dozens of overseas investors in Beijing and northern China
port city of Tianjin at two separate forums last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
