<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Major Trade News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Furniture Wood China '99, an international furniture and
woodworking machinery exhibition, is scheduled to be held in
Beijing from October 31 to November 3.
</P>
<P>
-- China has decided to lift the restrictions on who can take
the qualification test to become a certified trader and thrown it
open to anyone, instead of only to foreign trade companies, in a
bid to meet the increasing demand for such personnel, the MOFTEC
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- China's top aircraft manufacturer, the Aviation Industries
of China (AVIC), has decided to expand cooperation with its
European counterpart Airbus. The two companies has recently signed
a series of agreements on furthering cooperation in design and
manufacturing of civilian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
-- An exposition focusing on the burgeoning electronic commerce
and communications sector is to be staged for the first time ever
in the Chinese capital from September 6 to 9. The MOFTEC and the
Ministry of Information Industry (MII) are the two organizers of
the E-Commerce Expo '99, which will feature the development of
China's E-Commerce technologies and applications.
</P>
<P>
-- Local government officials and entrepreneurs across China
will be briefed on the latest developments in the country's bid to
enter the World Trade Organization (WTO) and the effect WTO entry
will have on China in a week-long seminar scheduled to begin on
July 18.
</P>
<P>
-- Bilateral trade and economic cooperation between China and
Japan will step into recovery. Customs statistics show the Sino-
Japanese trade volume declined by 4.8 percent to 57.9 billion U.S.
dollars during the 1997-98 period and Japanese investment also
slumped because of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- Two big Chinese supermarkets will soon be launched in Russia,
which are expected to boost Russian consumer's confidence in
Chinese goods. The preparatory work is proceeding well, an MOFTEC
official said. 
</P>
