<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Close Loss-Making Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China plans to close 40 coal
pits and force 14 additional state-owned coal mines into
bankruptcy during 1999 as part of the ongoing effort to
restructure the coal indutry.
</P>
<P>
China's coal industry has suffered from an excessive production
capacity over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Knowledgeable sources with the State Administration of Coal
Industry report that more than 120 state-owned coal mines are
operating in the red, with the total annual production capacity of
the operations standing at 90 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The mines produced over 50 million ton coals in 1998, with
total losses for the operations soaring to 3.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Mines scheduled for closure this year have a total annual
production capacity of 39 million tons and total assets of close
to 11.1 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
