<HEADLINE> "We Really Wanted to Win the Group" German Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- German coach Tina Thuene-Meyer
said her team really wanted to win the group after being held to a
3-3 draw by Brazil in their last group match on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We realized we played a defensive first half and it didn't
work. Then we decided to give everything in the second half because
we really wante to win the group." Thuene-Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
Thuene-Meyer said:"I think you see how we came out in the second
half, but eventually it didn't work out."
</P>
<P>
Thuene-Meyer said she had no game plan against the United States
by now:"I don't have one right now but I will have one on Thursday."
</P>
<P>
Germany will play the United States on July 1 at Washington:"I
am happy we don't have to move to another town. We can hae a rest.
We think we are tough enough to take another very good game." said
Thuene-Meyer.
</P>
<P>
Thuene-Meyer said her team was capable of beating any opponents
if they were in good form:"I think our team is strong that on a good
day we can beat any other team, including the United States and I
hope we show well on Thursday."
</P>
<P>
Brazilian coach Wilson De Oliveira Rica said he had expected the
match would be tough:"We know that every single one of the matches
would be tough, all of them were strong. Germany were European
champions."
</P>
<P>
"we can't play the American team in the quarterfinals now. But
inevitably we will have to face the Amierican team on eday in the
future." said Wilson De Oliveira Rica.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian star forward Sissi said the match against Germany
could be the most emotional game she had played:"At one point in the
game it looked like everything was going to go underwater, but we
listened to our coach and we kept our heads together and held our
faith and were able to score in the end." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
