<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Completes Restoration of Cultural Relics Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- An extensive project to restore and
refurbish a large number of cultural relics sites was recently
completed in southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The project is another major move to protect ancient historical
sites following the completion of the restoration and maintenance
project at the Potala Palace in Lhasa, the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
A team of 60-odd Tibetan and Han archeologists, craftsmen and
restoration experts repaired deteriorating historical building
covering 3,200 sq.m., reinforced 16 ancient buildings and restored
paintings covering a total area of 1,350 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The experts also discovered a number of frescos and retrieved a
large number of sculptures, and Tangka and Buddhist articles from
collapsed buildings.
</P>
<P>
The project was mainly carried out in Ali Prefecture and
primarily focused on protecting and maintaining relics site dating
to the Guge Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom, often referred to as the "Kingdom of Heaven", was
located at an altitude of some 5,000 meters above sea level. The
Guge Kingdom covered a vast area in Tibet stretching from modern-
day Lhasa to borders with Xinjiang, India, and Nepal. The
population reached as high as one million people between the mid-
10th and early 17th centuries.
</P>
<P>
The restoration project commenced in 1996 and was completed at
a total cost of 11.15 million yuan, including 10.18 million yuan
provided by the State Administration of Cultural Relics, 570,000
yuan by the regional government and 400,000 yuan from an American
philanthropist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990628.0231 </DOCNO>
