<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold Show for Archaeological Discoveries over Past 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition for China's
archaeological discoveries over the past five decades will be held
jointly by the National Museum of Chinese History and the Museum
of Chinese Revolutionary History from August 13 to October 17.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, entitled "China's Cultural Heritage 1949-99",
will be staged in the 1,100-square-meter hall linking the two
museums, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Li Ji, director of the Display Department of the National
Museum of Chinese History, said the exhibition is intended to
provide a rare opportunity for visitors to study the sites of some
major archaeological discoveries. Some 400 items will be on
display.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese archaeologists have pushed the boundary of knowledge
about prehistoric human activities back about one million years
over the past five decades," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The earliest relic site discovered in China before 1949 was the
Peking Man site at southwest Beijing's Zhoukoudian, which dates
back some 500,000 years.
</P>
<P>
Fifty years later, the most ancient cultural relics are more
than 1.7 million years old, discovered in Yuanmou, Yunnan Province,
Li added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
